<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Peace Talks on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday called for peace talks to seek a political
settlement in the restless Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In his report, issued here on Monday, to the U.N. Security
Council, he said, "Full and unconditional acceptance of peaceful
negotiations is the only way to resolve the crisis in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Annan made the appeals as preparations for the U.S.-led NATO
air strike on the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
"I therefore once again urge the parties to engage in
negotiations on a peaceful settlement in Kosovo without further
delay and without preconditions, as demanded by the international
community and in particular," by relevant Security Council
resolutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The six-nation Contact Group on January 29 decided to summon
representatives of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and the
Republic of Serbia and of the Kosovo Albanians to Rambouillet,
southwest of Paris, by February 6, to begin negotiations.
</P>
<P>
So far, none of the parties has said "no" to the peace offer,
contained in a joint statement issued at the end of a meeting of
foreign ministers of the Contact Group members in London. However,
none of the parties has indicated their full acceptance of the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan said that the criminals who committed the
reported January 15 massacre in the village of Racak, southern
Kosovo, should be brought to justice in order to restore peace in
the restless Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative that the perpetrators be brought to justice
in order to deter further violence and to give peace in Kosovo a
chance," Annan said in a report, issued here on Monday, to the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"Any appearance of impunity for the perpetrators could become a
real obstacle to the process of finding a peaceful solution to the
conflict through negotiation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief, who earlier said he was "shocked and dismayed"
by the massacre reports, also urged that "unconditional respect be
given to the authority of the International Tribune for the Former
Yugoslavia throughout all of the territory of the former
Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
The European monitor mission reported on January 16 that 45
ethnic Albanians were found killed in the village of Racak,
touching off strong response from the international community.
</P>
<P>
"Fear of fighting between the security forces and Kosovo
Albanian paramilitary units and continued violence against
civilians are the overriding obstacle to return and to the
sustainability of those returns that have taken place," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The humanitarian operation has demonstrated its capacity to
deliver large-scale assistance, but without an end to violence and
the establishment of a climate of security this will not suffice,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am increasingly concerned that the spread of violence and
the nature of the attacks could lead to a situation of all-out
civil war in Kosovo, which might have unpredictable repercussions
for the entire region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Violence, from whatever quarter, can only lead to further
suffering for the civilians population in Kosovo, which has been
the main target and victim of the conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts broke out in Kosovo in February last year after
ethnic Albanians, who make up some 90 percent of the province's
population of 2 million, fought with Serbs for independence.
</P>
</TEXT>
