<HEADLINE> OPEC Oil Prices Edges Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The average price of OPEC's
basket of seven crudes edged up to 10.75 U.S. dollars per barrel
last week, from 10.54 dollars the week before.
</P>
<P>
The Vienna-based Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) Secretariat announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The price climbed above 11 dollars per barrel during the first
two weeks of January because of a decline in the inventory of some
major oil consumption countries.
</P>
<P>
The average price for the whole of 1998 dived by a third to 12.
28 dollars from 1997. In December, the price slumped to below 10.
00 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that oil prices on the world market might recover
in the near future because of the bitter cold weather which has
swept through a number of regions recently and has increased the
need for heating oil.
</P>
<P>
However, they forecast that the recovery will not be big
because the oversupply of oil has not seen any fundamental changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
