<HEADLINE> France's Societe Generale and Paribas to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- France's two major banks, the
Societe Generale (SG) and Paribas, said on Monday that they will
merge in an overall restructuring of European banking system.
</P>
<P>
Societe Generale has launched an offer for shares in Paribas to
create a new banking entity named SG Paribas.
</P>
<P>
The merger, whose cost is estimated at 15.1 billion euros (17
billion U.S. dollars), would create the fourth-biggest bank in the
world in terms of shareholders' funds of 21 billion euros (24
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new banking group will replace Credit Agricole as France's
biggest banking group and will be on the same scale as the
Deutsche Bank AG and Swiss UBS.
</P>
<P>
French Minister of Finance and Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn
welcomed the move by the two banks as ``a strong and dynamic
French financial sector at the heart of the euro.''
</P>
<P>
The head of Paribas, Andre Levy-Lang, will chair the new group
and the president of SG, Daniel Bouton, will become vice president
and succeed Levy-Lang in 2002.
</P>
<P>
``The objective is to achieve recurrent profitability on
shareholders' funds of 15 percent of net profits per share of more
than 15 percent per year on average,'' said the two banks in a
joint communique.
</P>
<P>
On the condition that Paribas will offer more than 50.01
percent of its shares in tendering, Societe Generale has offered
to buy all Paribas shares with every five SG shares for eight
Paribas shares, which would involve 96 million out of the total of
196 shares of Society Generale.
</P>
<P>
SG said that it would offer a 17 percent premium above the
Paribas share price over the past 20 trading days during the
operation, which will be from February 9 till March 16.
</P>
<P>
The new group will have six main areas of business: retail
banking, special financial services, banking services and asset
management, shareholdings, and property.
</P>
<P>
SG Paribas will also be the leader in international investment
banking activities, ranking among the world's top five in
eurobonds, derivatives, and international trade finance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
