<HEADLINE> Israeli Companies Win Bid for Cyprus' Desalination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli joint venture has
won the bid to build Cyprus' second desalination plant, Cyprus'
Agriculture, Natural Resources and Environment Minister Costas
Themistocleous announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The tender was won by the joint venture of two Israeli
companies, Ide and OCEANA. The Cyprus government will buy water
from the joint venture at the price of 42.2 Cyprus cents per cubic
metre (about 85 U.S. cents).
</P>
<P>
According to the Minister, in less than two years, all
households in Cyprus will have constant supply of water.
</P>
<P>
Themistocleous said resevoirs in Cyprus now have 30 million
cubic metres of water, only about 11 percent of their total
capacity, far behind the amount of water needed for the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
