<HEADLINE> Americans at U.N. Seek Parity With Foreign Co-workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A group of American
citizens working for the United Nations in professional-level jobs
are preparing to step up a fight to receive the same education
grants for their children that foreign officials get in New York.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement more than 50 years old, foreign
professionals working at the United Nations headquarters here as
specialists in a range of fields including economics, political
affairs and technical or financial services receive more than
15,500 U.S. dollars a year for each child in school in New York,
the New York Times, a major U.S. newspaper, said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Americans do not get the grants, which were intended to allow
foreign families to pay for a private education in language or
culture of their home countries, so that the children could return
comfortably to those nations.
</P>
<P>
"It wouldn't be so bad if it were sued for the purpose
intended," an American working here said. The reality, this
official and others from various countries said, is that the grant
buys entry to the best private schools and colleges for children
who may have been born in this country, have an American parent or
be part of a family settled here.
</P>
<P>
"What makes it so unjust is that many of these children are
Americans like our children," an American parent said. The
Americans -- about 108 officials with a total of more than 170
children -- want help from United Nations representatives on the
United Nations committee that determines these grants, said
Stephen Baldwin, who recently retired as an official in the
Department of Economic and Social Affairs.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Baldwin was among a group of Americans who petitioned
the United Nations Administrative Tribunal, the organization's
highest judicial panel, for equal treatment. They were turned
down.
</P>
<P>
Baldwin suggested in an interview with the newspaper that the
General Assembly, the group of 185 nations that formally sets the
grant levels, could freeze increases until the Americans could be
brought into the program. This would not add costs to the
organization's already hamstrung budget.
</P>
<P>
The United States, unlike many other nations, is perennially
reluctant to become involved in the cases of Americans working for
the United Nations, officials said.
</P>
<P>
"It would be very helpful to us if our own representatives were
to take up this case and say this isn't a level playing field,"
Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
Another parent, who did not want to be identified, said the
American Governement's attitude "represents the low esteem with
which the United Nations is held in Washington."
</P>
<P>
Some American officials have recommended abolishing the grant
entirely, but Baldwin said that this would be politically
unrealistic and "draconian," because many families are involved
who do sent their children to foreign-language schools and need
financial help living in New York. Average salaries for these
professional-level jobs hover around 75,000 U.S. dollars and
80,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The education grant has become an untaxed windfall for
foreigners, augmenting their salaries substantially, American
professionals say.
</P>
<P>
The grants apply only to United Nations officials, whose
salaries and benefits are set or reviewed by the General Assembly
and the International Civil Service Commission. The supplements do
not apply to diplomats based in foreign missions in New York,
though they may qualify for other programs through their
respective governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
