<HEADLINE> Pakistani Government to Continue Its Afghan Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
decided at a high-level meeting Monday to continue with its
present policy of encouraging the Afghan people to find a lasting
solution to the Afghan issue among themselves.
</P>
<P>
The meeting presided by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was held in
Lahore, the country's second largest city, and was attended by,
among others, Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz, State Minister for
Foreign Affairs Siddiq Khan Kanju, Chief of Army Staff Gen. Pervez
Musharraf, the Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) reported.
</P>
<P>
APP quoted Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed as saying that the
meeting decided that "Pakistan's Afghan policy is sound," and it
will continue to promote peace efforts in the war-torn country in
collaboration with its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, he said, discussed the outcome of Pakistan's
high-level contacts with the Central Asian countries and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad urged the United Nations to stop the inflow of arms
into Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He also said Pakistan would continue to be in touch with Saudi
Arabia, Iran and Six Plus two (Afghanistan's six immediate
neighbors plus Russia and the United States) to do whatever it can
for promotion of peace in Afghanistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
