<HEADLINE> Clinton Proposes 1.77 Trillion Dollars Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Clinton sent
Congress a 1.77 trillion U.S. dollars spending plan Monday for the
fiscal year of 2000, beginning a new century with record budget
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton, proclaiming his budget marks a" new era of
opportunity," proposed increasing spending for the fiscal year
that begins next Oct. 1 by 2.3 percent. Even with the 39 billion
dollars increase over the current year, the new budget projects a
record 117 billion dollars surplus.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's plan forecasts 2.41 trillion dollars in surpluses
over the next decade, laying out a vision of plenty the country
has not known in 70 years.
</P>
<P>
President's budget was the opening shot in what is expected to
be a bitter struggle with the Republican-controlled Congress over
government priorities.
</P>
<P>
Republicans seek an across-the-board 10 percent cut in income
tax rates, returning 600 billion dollars or more to taxpayers over
the next decade. That, they say, is critical to keep the Democrats
from creating new spending programs.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's proposals require approval by Congress, and it's
unclear how eager the two sides will be to reach compromise given
the impeachment battle and a looming presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the call for hundreds of billions in
across-the-board tax cuts, Clinton's budget offers targeted tax
relief of 36.2 billion dollars over five years.
</P>
<P>
This includes a 1,000 dollars tax credit to help people handle
long-term health care costs, and a 250 dollars credit for
stay-at-home parents caring for infants below the age of 1.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's budget also includes several proposals that
Republicans have rejected in past years _ including a
55-cent-a-pack increase in cigarette taxes. The president would
raise 53.4 billion dollars over five years from that.
</P>
<P>
As first outlined in his State of the Union speech, Clinton
proposed using 62 percent of the 4.85 trillion dollars in
projected surpluses over the next 15 years to shore up Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
Republicans agree that much of the surplus should be set aside
for the retirement of 76 million baby boomers, although they
disagree with the president on the best way to do this.
</P>
<P>
But the big fight will be over what to do with the rest of the
projected surpluses. Clinton wants to devote the rest to support
Medicare, provide additional spending for the military and
domestic programs and set up new retirement accounts to funnel 36
billion dollars annually into individuals' savings.
</P>
<P>
Clinton proposed a 280.8 billion dollars defense budget for
2000, including 53 billion dollars for hi-teck weapons.
</P>
<P>
the 280.8 billion dollars, which includes 13.6 billion for the
Energy Department and others with military responsibility, was a
slight increase over the 276.2 billion dollars requested for 1999.
</P>
<P>
In Clinton's 2000 budget projects, the government will collect
1.88 trillion dollars in revenues, up 4.3 percent from the current
year. The 117 billion dollars surplus for 2000 follows a projected
79 billion dollars surplus this year and an actual 69 billion
dollars surplus realized in 1998, the first year the government
had finished in the black in 29 years.
</P>
<P>
The 2.41 trillion dollars in total surpluses the administration
envisions is about 160 billion below the amount forecast by the
nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office. The administration's
forecast foresees growth of 2 percent or above over the next five
years with no recession in sight, even though the current
expansion is already the longest in peacetime history.
</P>
<P>
Economists caution the budget surpluses could vanish if the
economy starts to turn sour.
</P>
<P>
Among highlights of Clinton's budget:
</P>
<P>
--Billions dollars more for the Pentagon over the next five
years although spending would actually go down in 2000. For the
entire period, Clinton proposes billions in new weapons purchases
and the largest pay raise for the military in two decades.
</P>
<P>
--5 billion dollars to build and renovate schools and hire
teachers. Clinton would tie part of that for the first time to
requirements that states upgrade the academic quality of their
weakest schools.
</P>
<P>
--5.3 billion dollars for health care initiatives over the next
five years, including expanding access to Medicare to people below
the current 65-year eligibility age. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
