<HEADLINE> Two Israelis Put Into Prison in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Two Israelis were sentenced to
three and a half years in prison in Cyprus Monday for approaching
a prohibited military area and possessing banned listening
equipment without due permission.
</P>
<P>
Igal Damary, 49, and Udi Hargov, 37, were arrested in early
November last year at the small fishing village of Zigi on the
Cypriot southern coast and found carrying radio scanners, a
lap-top computer, cell phones and eight maps of the island.
</P>
<P>
The village is near military installations, including an army
commando training camp.
</P>
<P>
After Damary and Hargov were arrested, the Israeli government,
U.S. Senators and European officials pressed Cyprus to drop the
espionage charges against them, claiming that the two Israelis
were in Cyprus for an anti-terrorist operation that was not aimed
at the Island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
