<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Rejects Seperation of Lebanese-Syrian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim
Hoss said on Monday that the Israeli attempt to separate Lebanese
and Syrian tracks in the peace process is doomed to fail.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that pursuing the entwinement of the
Lebanese-Israeli and the Syrian-Israeli peace making tracks is a
final resolution of the two countries as well as a guarantee for
Lebanon against Israeli aggression.
</P>
<P>
Hoss' remarks came in a response to Israeli Foreign Minister
Ariel Sharon's comments on Sunday that it is wrong to link the
Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon with the resumption of its
negotiations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Sharon also said that Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon should
not be contingent upon a deal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Talks between Israel and Syria over returning the strategic
Golan Heights to Syria, which Israel captured in the 1967 Middle
East war, have been suspended since 1996 after the hard-line Likud
government of Benjamin Netanyahu came to power.
</P>
<P>
Israel accused Syria, which has 40,000 troops deployed in
Lebanon, of holding the security zone as a bargaining chip to seek
an Israeli full withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
