<HEADLINE> Iran Marks Revolution Anniversary Amid Intensified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran started on Monday
celebrations of the 20th anniversary of the Islamic revolution
amid intensified power struggles and concerns over the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
School bells rang and helicopters showered flowers on the
shrine of Ayatollah Ruhollah Musavi Khomeini, founder of the
Islamic Republic, to mark his return from a 15-year exile the same
day 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
A large crowd gathered inside the shrine to pay tribute to
Khomeini, who masterminded the Islamic revolution which toppled
the former pro-U.S. Pahlavi regime in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the crowd, former Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani called for unity among the people despite their
differences.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that national solidarity must be protected as
extremist actions should be avoided and speeches aiming at
dividing national unity should be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives and the moderates of the country have been
engaged in a heated political quarrel since the revelation of the
involvement of some agents of the conservative-controlled
Intelligence Ministry in the murders of several dissident
intellectuals late last year.
</P>
<P>
The moderates called for a fundamental change in the ministry,
but the conservatives counter attacked by accusing supporters of
moderate President Mohammad Khatami of being behind the murders.
</P>
<P>
The quarrel was intensified with the approaching of the
elections of local councils of cities and villages slated on
February 26.
</P>
<P>
The pro-moderate Interior Ministry, which is responsible for
holding elections, and the conservative-dominated election
supervisory committee blast each other of siding certain factions.
</P>
<P>
In Tehran, the supervisory committee disqualified some 50
moderate candidates for the elections, reportedly including former
Interior Minister Abdullah Nouri, who was impeached by the
conservative Majlis (parliament) last June.
</P>
<P>
The move irritated the Interior Ministry and disappointed the
public, the young generation in particular, who pinned their hope
on Khatami's moderate supporters for a better future.
</P>
<P>
Badly hit by oil price fall, economic situation of the country
has become more and more worrying.
</P>
<P>
Rial, the Iranian currency, lost about 15 percent of its value
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
On Tehran's illegal but highly active black market, the
U.S. dollar was traded at 8,300 rials on Monday, from 7,100 rials
at the beginning of last month.
</P>
<P>
Many economists said the country would face a serious economic
recession this year as the future of oil prices is still dim.
</P>
<P>
"If people observe unity and step onto a single road, they can
overcome every kind of difficulties," Rafsanjani told the people
at Khomeini's shrine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
