<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Back NATO in Event of Strike in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria would back NATO in the
event of a military strike against Yugoslavia to end the fighting
in Kosovo, Bulgarian President Petar Stoyanov said in Monday's
edition of the daily Berliner Morgenpost.
</P>
<P>
"I'm certain that the international community will use every
means to find a peaceful solution to the conflict in Kosovo.
That's what all the neighboring states want," Stoyanov said.
</P>
<P>
However, if there were military strikes, Bulgaria would "pursue
a policy of Euro-Atlantic solidarity", Stoyanov said.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov reiterated his call for Bulgaria to be granted
membership in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) as
soon as it has met the necessary criteria.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the former Yugoslavia could be stabilized
better if Bulgaria, Romania and Macedonia were NATO members,
Stoyanov said. The instability of Yugoslavia was harming the image
of the entire region, he added.
</P>
<P>
In mid-January, Britain made it clear that it would support
Bulgaria's efforts to join the Atlantic alliance saying it was not
a question of whether Bulgaria should join, but of when.  
</P>
