<HEADLINE> Russia Welcomes U.N. Statement on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry on
Monday welcomed a U.N. resolution on Kosovo and expressed its full
support.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the document, made Friday by the chairman of
the U.N. Security Council following the foreign ministers' meeting
of the six-nation Contact Group, "is oriented to political methods
of tackling Kosovo's problems and to the acceleration of talks
with active participation of the Contact Group and of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. statement confirms the "adherence (of the United
Nations) to the sovereignty and territorial integrity of
Yugoslavia, and the need to seek solutions on the basis of
equality of rights and respect for the legitimate interests of all
Kosovo ethnic communities," the Interfax news agency quoted a
ministry spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russia believes "the U.N. Security Council has stated in clear
terms that it will keep the process of settlement in Kosovo under
its strict political control."
</P>
<P>
"This is a clear signal to all those who are advocating the use
of force and, concurrently, seek a redistribution of roles
undermining U. N. authority," the spokesman said, apparently
referring to NATO's threat of military actions.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a senior Russian defense official on
Monday express concern over a recent document authorizing NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana to order air strikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued Saturday by the NATO Council, means the
military alliance still regards armed force as the most effective
means of resolving the Kosovo conflict, Gen. Col. Leonid Ivashov,
head of the ministry's international cooperation department, said.
</P>
<P>
"In effect, the role of the OSCE and the U.N. Security Council
is being eroded."
</P>
<P>
However, Ivanov noted some "progress" in NATO's line in parts
of the statement, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
The document, he said, is putting equal pressure on both the
Yugoslav government and the ethnic Albanian separatists.
</P>
<P>
The NATO statement said Solana will take account of the Kosovo
Albanians' behavior in considering air attacks, and that the
alliance is looking for ways to prevent smuggling weapons into the
breakaway Yugoslav province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
