<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report on Early Warning of Africa's Environmental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A report named " Early Warning
of Selected Emerging Environmental Issues in Africa ", published
by the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP), was made to the
public here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report identifies some emerging environmental issues facing
Africa by examining the inter-connected nature of population
dynamics, land cover distribution, protected areas and
trans-boundary water resources.
</P>
<P>
In the forward of the report, UNEP Executive Director Klaus
Toepfer said this report conveys a sense of urgency about the need
to develop suitable long-term strategies, attract investments and
stimulate international cooperation to conserve biodiversity and
fresh-water resources.
</P>
<P>
The report carries major findings of the study and suggested
policy responses.
</P>
<P>
About 63 percent of the total land in Africa lies within
trans-boundary river basins and five of the river baisn (The
Congo, Nile, Niger, Chad and Zambezi) occupy some 42 percent of
geographical area and sustain 44 percent of the African
population.
</P>
<P>
It says that in the interests of sustainable development, the
ripairan states should cooperate and develop collaborative
infrastructures for the scientific management of their shared
eco-systems.
</P>
<P>
The presence of crop land in protected areas show that legal
designation alone is not sufficient for the protection of
biodiversity in the face of human competition for the same land,
the report says, adding that the local shareholders should be
given economic incentives and a role in the conservation of
biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
The report also noted that a shift in national and
international policy and planning, based on targeting
biodiversity-rich areas, is needed for enhanced and effective
protection and conservation.
</P>
<P>
It emphasizes that it is imperative that the contradictions in
 approach and conflicts of interest of parties concerned should be
 harmonized in the interest of developing an effective
collaborative management for the protected areas with multi-party
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
The report, part of UNEP's efforts to strength its early
warning and assessment functions, is being discussed at the
ongoing five-day UNEP Governing Council session, which opened here
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
