<HEADLINE> Solana Arrived in Germany to Talk on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The German government warned
Serbia and the Kosovar Albanians on Monday that they must
negotiate and reach agreement on autonomy for the southern Serb
province of Kosovo and on ending the violence there.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after a meeting with the
Secretary-General of the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation
(NATO), Javier Solana, Schroeder said Germany stood firmly behind
the ultimatum issued to the Serbs and Kosovar Albanians by the
six-power Balkans contact group.
</P>
<P>
He said, the international community was "deadly earnest" in
its demands that the parties to the conflict should reach
agreement within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said, Germany was "ready for all eventualities" in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the contact group countries meeting
in London on January 29 called on Yugoslav leaders and Albanian
Kosovars to meet on February 6 in France and to reach an interim
peace agreement two weeks after that.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said Yugoslav president Slobodan Milosevic had to
understand that the ultimatum had to be observed "to the minute".
</P>
<P>
Solana made today a one-day visit to Germany to discuss Kosovo
with the German government. He also talked with German Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer and Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping.
</P>
<P>
Fischer told the press conference that if Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic did not make concessions, "the consequences
will be too serious to speculate about".
</P>
<P>
He presumed Belgrade would send a high-ranking delegation to
the scene of the talks at Rambouillet, near Paris, which was
authorized to complete an agreement.
</P>
<P>
He added that the German armed forces had begun training
additional troops for possible deployment in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Scharping had told Solana that Germany would make available a
"strengthened" battalion of 800 men. This unit would, if
necessary, back up the 350 Germans in the 1,800-strong
international force in Macedonia which was ready to ensure the
security of the 2,000 unarmed OSCE observers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Solana said NATO was both politically and militarily prepared
if the conflicting parties did not appear at the negotiating table
at Rambouillet on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
No new formal decision would be needed if a military attack
were needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Solana and Schroeder emphasised the constructive role of
Russia both in the contact group and the United Nations Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
The Balkans contact group comprises the United States, Russia,
Britain, France, Germany and Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
