<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Team Begins Probe Into 1994 Rwandan Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 1 (Xinhua) -- An International Panel of
Eminent Personalities (IPEP) has begun investigation into the 1994
genocide in Rwanda which claimed the lives of more than 500,000
Tutsis and Hutu moderates.
</P>
<P>
The panel arrived in Kigali, capital of Rwanda, Sunday, on a
five-day fact-finding mission aimed at finding out the truth about
the Rwandan genocide and surrounding events which rocked the Great
Lakes region, according to a report reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Their research will go as far back as August 1993, when the
Arusha peace agreement was signed, and will cover the period
extending to the first Congolese rebellion which culminated into
the fall of the dictatorial regime of President Mobutu Sese Seko
in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
''The object of our visit to Rwanda is to come and meet the
people of Rwanda and try to find out events which led to the
genocide,'' IPEP chairman, former president of Botswana Ketumile
Masire told the Rwanda News Agency upon arrival in Kigali Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Apart from meeting government officials, the panel will also
talk to genocide survivors and visit some important genocide sites
where thousands of Tutsis were butchered. They will then visit
other countries in the Great Lakes Region, in Europe, the United
States, and Canada before drafting the conclusions to hand to the
heads of state of Organization of African Unity (OAU) member
countries.
</P>
<P>
The panel was established by the OAU summit held in Ouagadougou
last June, and its work was officially inaugurated by OAU
Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim, and Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi last Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
