Schroeder welcomed Moscow's desire to develop, together with
the European Union, the economic structures in Russia necessary
for a greater economic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The Russian minister's discussions with Schroeder dealt chiefly
with preparations for the chancellor's visit to Moscow on February
18 and 19.
</P>
<P>
Germany is currently chairing the EU.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder intends to discuss with the Russian leadership the
expansion of bilateral ties as well as Russia's relations with the
EU.
</P>
<P>
In Cologne in June, the EU is scheduled to approve a joint
strategy towards Russia.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said the contents of the strategy have already been
settled: the EU wants not only improved economic cooperation with
Russia, but also comprehensive political cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Kosovo, Ivanov said Russia regarded a
solution to the conflict from the viewpoint of establishing a new
security program for Europe.
</P>
<P>
Germany and Russia had, in that respect, common strategic aims,
not only as far as the Kosovo problem was concerned, Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia is ready to enter into the closest possible partnership
cooperation in order to counter all the risks and challenges
appropriately," he said.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder noted the determination of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organisation (NATO) and Russia to contribute in "different ways"
towards a political settlement of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
Both NATO and Russia took the view that Serbs and Kosovo
Albanians would come to the negotiating table, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
Russia had played, in the six-nation international Contact
Group on the Balkans, a role which Schroeder said he "very highly
esteemed". That role had been "constructive and certainly
contributed towards increasing the chances of a sensible
settlement in Kosovo".
</P>
<P>
Ivanov is in Bonn for two days of talks, including a meeting
with his German counterpart, Joschka Fischer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
