<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Report Stresses Environmental Impact of Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Many small wild fires have
quickly escalated into large-scale and uncontrolled disasters in
recent two years, affecting adversly the environment and people,
according to a report released by the United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report titled "Wildland Fires and the Environment: a Globe
Synthesis" provides an overview of the causes, impacts, and some
potential means for the international community to respond to
widespread forest and other wild fires.
</P>
<P>
It reveals that the gaseous and particulate emissions from the
1997 fires in Indonesia significantly exceeded those from the
Kuwaiti oil fires in 1991, another major environmental
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
Most of the fires were set by locals for land clearing. Many
others were caused by extreme drought conditions related to the
1997 El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
In Southeast Asia alone, tens of millions of people were
exposed to high levels of fire-produced gases and particulates for
weeks at a time. The poor atmospheric visibility resulting from
the fires was responsible for the crash of a commercial airplane
and the collision of two ships. It will take years to measure
long-term negative impacts on the region's biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
Gases produced by fire include carbon dioxide and methane which
are greenhouse gases that lead to global warming. Other gases are
chemically active and lead to the photo-chemical production of
ozone near ground. Ground level ozone is a pollutant with a
adverse impact on all living systems.
</P>
<P>
Fire also produces large amounts of particulate matter. These
small solid particles absorb and scatter incoming solar radiation
and impact planetary climate systems. In addition, smoke
particulates smaller than about 2.5 micrometers can easily enter
the human respiratory system with resultant health problems, said
the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
