<HEADLINE> Egypt, France to Hold Talks on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and his French counterpart Jacques Chirac will hold talks on the
latest developments of the Middle East peace process, Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the discussions will be based on the initiative
declared by the two leaders last year for holding an international
conference to promote the Mideast peacemaking, the Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who arrived in Paris earlier in the day from Davos,
Switzerland, where he attended the World Economic Forum, will hold
talks with Chirac Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The proposal "still stands" and is "applicable and viable,"
Moussa said, stressing that it should be put into practice in case
the peace process continues to be stalled.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks suffered another setback
after Israel in early December froze the latest peace deal, the Wye
River agreement.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that Mubarak and Chirac will also touch on the
peace negotiations on the Israeli-Syrian and Israeli-Lebanese
tracks.
</P>
<P>
"The talks will also cover the Lebanese and Syrian tracks with
the aim to reach durable and comprehensive peace in the region,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations between Syria and Israel came to a halt in
early 1996 due to disputes over the future of the Golan Heights
which Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Moussa expressed Egypt's readiness to cooperate with European
counties to help advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt will intensify efforts and contacts with the European
states to break the peace deadlock," said the Egyptian minister.
</P>
