<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Apapa Port Handles 6.91 Million Tons of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Apapa Port in Lagos
handled a total of 6.91 million tons of cargoes in 1998, an
increase of 39 percent compared with a cargo throughput of 4.97
million tons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The port's ship traffic position showed that the port handled
3.34 million tons of cargoes in the first half of last year and
3.57 million tons in the second half, the News Agency of Nigeria
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown of the figures indicated that the total inward
cargo throughput in 1998 was 6.61 million tons while the total
outward cargo throughput was 308,546 tons.
</P>
<P>
The throughput of inward cargoes for 1998 comprised 2.94
million tons of dry bulk and 3.48 million tons of liquid bulk
while that of outward cargoes consisted of 281,440 tons of dry
bulk and 13,037 tons of liquid bulk.
</P>
<P>
The Apapa Port received 922 ships in 1998, as against 822 ships
which berthed at the port in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The tonnages of ships that entered the port in the first and
second halves of 1998 were 3.48 million tons and 3.88 million tons
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Port manager Ngozi Duru was quoted as saying at the weekend
that if there is any problem for the port, "it is that of
inadequate berthing space to cope with the upsurge in ships coming
into the port." 
</P>
</TEXT>
