<HEADLINE> Moldova: Prime Minister's Resignation Accepted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Moldovan President Petru
Lucinschi accepted late on Monday the resignation of the Prime
Minister Ion Ciubuc.
</P>
<P>
According to Rompres news agency, the President has already
begun consultations with the parliamentary groups to highlight a
candidate for the office of prime minister. The prerogative to
move a candidature for this post belongs to the head of the state,
as it is stipulated in the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Ion Ciubuc tendered his resignation early in the day. In
compliance with the constitution, his move signifies the
resignation of all the cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference in the government residence, Ion Ciubuc
designated the impossibility for the government to work under the
circumstances of the proposed power algorithm as the main motive
for his deed. In his opinion, a coalition government must build
its performance on principles of mutual understanding and respect,
but "There was always a lack of them," Ciubuc said with regret.
</P>
<P>
Ciubuc's center-right government was sworn in last May but
proved unable to deal with the economic difficulties provoked by
the impact of the Russian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ciubuc refused to speak about his successor, but noted that
Depute Prime Ministers Ion Sturza and Nicolae Andronic, as well as
Minister for Agriculture and Processing Industry Valeriu Bulgari
have energetic teams for forming a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
However, he called Chisinau mayor Serafim Urecheanu as the most
probable candidacy for the position.
</P>
<P>
He did not ruled out a probable participation by the Party of
Communists in the future government. "It depends on the candidacy
for the prime minister and forces, which will participate in the
formation of the cabinet," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The current parliamentary majority -- the Alliance for
Democracy and Reforms, formed after the election in last March,
consists of three of the four parliamentary factions, the
Democratic Convention, the Democratic and Prosperous Moldova Bloc
and the Party of Democratic Forces. The Party of Communists, which
ranked the first in election, became the only opposition in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The candidacy is to be presented late this week to the
parliament for approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
