<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Government Urged to Implement Stated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe Financial Holdings
(Finhold) Monday urged the government to timeously implement its
stated policies, while maintaining dialog with the private sector
in order to restore confidence in the economy this year.
</P>
<P>
In its 1998 Zimbabwe Economic Review, Finhold, a local
financial group, said that the past year was very difficult with
all economic indicators deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
It noted that consultations with all stakeholders, as was seen
with the formation of the National Economic Consultative Forum and
the tripartite (the government, business and labour movement)
negotiation forum, need to be strengthened in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Such consultative frameworks should help to reduce policy
conflicts and result in easier implementation of the agreed
policies since all stakeholders will have been involved in the
designing stages," it said.
</P>
<P>
One key remedy for the deteriorating economic indicators,
Finhold said, is for the government to reduce its budget deficit
as this will reduce recourse to the monetary banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Year-on-year inflation as measured by the consumer price index
has reached an all time high of 46.6 percent for December, 1998
while interest rates are hovering above 41 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe has indicated in its latest
economic bulletin that money supply growth rose from 17.8 percent
in October, last year to 27.1 in November, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Growth in exports will have to be part of a strategy designed
to stabilise the Zimbabwean dollar in the long run," it said.
</P>
