<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life May Have Arisen 3.7 Billion Years Ago: Researcher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A Danish researcher said
that life could have arisen 3.7 billion years ago, pushing back
the beginning of life further than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
Reporting in the latest issue of Science, Minik T. Rosin from
the Danish Lithosphere Center in Copenhagen said that he came to
the conclusion after analyzing the carbon content of microscopic
globules of graphite retrieved from rocks in western Greenland
dating back 3.7 billion years.
</P>
<P>
Rosin found the levels of various types of carbon, the basis of
all life on Earth, indicating that some type of marine creature,
perhaps a type of plankton, existed at that time.
</P>
<P>
He said that the oldest known fossils of extremely primitive
forms of bacteria date back 3.5 billion years, but life may have
existed before leaving behind fossils that were later destroyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0044 </DOCNO>
