diplomatic activities over the last week including the Contact
Group announcement and the NATO ultimatum," Leavy said. "They'll
review the situation on the ground, then brief the president on
additional consultations from last week and how we proceed
forward," he added.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the Contact Groups -- the United States,
Russia, Britain, Germany and Iraly -- agreed on Friday to order
Serbs and ethnic Albanians to go to France by February 6 to begin
negotiations, setting a tight deadline for concluding a peace deal
between them.
</P>
<P>
NATO cleared the way on Saturday for the use of force to help
impose a deal on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Leavy said major decisions were not expected from Clinton's
meeting with his advisers and any decision on U.S. troops
participating in a peacekeeping force for Kosovo once a peace
deal is reached is some time away.
</P>
<P>
"There have been a lot of important questions raised about a
post-implementation force, what the mission would be, what the
exit strategy would be, and I'm sure those questions will be
raised with the president," Leavy said.  
