designation, the reports quoted spokeswoman Jennifer George as
saying. She also said the hospital was expecting six to eight more
people.
</P>
<P>
University of Michigan Hospital spokeswoman Carol Craig said
its medical helicopter was heading to the scene.
</P>
<P>
Dearborn police cordoned off the area around the plant and said
they were being cautious because they feared there could be a
second explosion, an officer who wouldn't give his name said.
</P>
<P>
The 445-hectare Rouge facility was once the world's largest
auto plant. Henry Ford built the plant in 1918 because he dreamed
of building a car from start to finish in one location.
</P>
<P>
At its peak in the 1940s, 85,000 people worked at the plant in
Dearborn, about 11 kilometers west of Detroit. About 8,000 people
work at the six Ford factories still in operation at the Rouge,
and Ford builds the Mustang there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Calls for Emergent Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Government of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY) has called for an emergency
session of the U.N. Security Council on Kosovo in order to
"prevent aggressions" against the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was contained in a letter on Monday from Zivadin
Jovanovic, foreign minister of the FRY, to the president of the
Security Council for the month of February, Robert Fowler of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
"I call on you to inform all Council members of this letter and
to convene an emergency session of the Council in order to take
appropriate measures available under the (U.N.) Charter to prevent
aggressions against my country," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
"The decision by NATO, as a regional agency, to have its
Secretary General authorize air strikes against targets on FRY
territory, as well as the position contained in the letter that
this was a 'final warning', represent an open and clear threat of
aggression against the FRY as a sovereign and independent Member
State of the United Nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, NATO's threat directly undermines the sovereignty
and territorial integrity of the FRY and flagrantly violates the
principles enshrined in the U.N. charters," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government's appeal was prompted by NATO's Saturday
decision to authorize its Secretary General Javier Solana to
order possible air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
As a regional organization, NATO, without the formal
authorization from the Security Council, has no right to launch
military action against Yugoslavia, an independent and sovereign
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
