<HEADLINE> France Denies Involvement in Guinea-Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- France denied on Tuesday that the
French navy shelled a rebel position in Guinea Bissau, as claimed
by the Guinea-Bissau government.
</P>
<P>
"We denied the rumor that the 'Siroco' had opened fire after
being attacked," said Francois Rivasseau, an assistant spokesman
for the French Foreign Ministry Francois Rivasseau.
</P>
<P>
The vice-prime minister of Guinea-Bissau Francisco Fadul told
national radio of Portugal that the French warship, which was
carrying 300 Western African peacekeeping soldiers, shelled the
rebel position, killing many people.
</P>
<P>
Rivasseau said the "Siroco," however, is only a transport ship
that does not have the equipment to bomb the coast.
</P>
<P>
The "Siroco" has tried but failed to get close to the coast due
to the heavy fighting between the government forces and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
France has condemned the fighting and called on the two sides
to stop and renew dialogues in the framework of the Abuja peace
agreement, which was signed last November, the spokesman added.
</P>
</TEXT>
