<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urgent: Brazil Replaces Its Central Bank President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, February 2 (Xinhua)-- Brazil's President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso Tuesday dismissed the president of
Brazil's Central Bank Francisco Lopes 18 days after he was
nominated to the post.
</P>
<P>
Lopes will be replaced by Arminio Fraga Neto, advisor of the
Soros Fundation run by international financier George Soros.
</P>
<P>
The change of the Central Bank president led a fluctuation from
one dollar against 1.82 to 1.84 reals.
</P>
<P>
The removal of Francisco Lopes, does not ``represent any
alteration in the current floating exchange rate system nor in the
overall economic policy guidelines, which will be maintained,''the
Finance Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Until Fraga is confirmed by the Congress, Demostenes Madureira
de Pinho of the central bank will serve as interim president.
</P>
<P>
Since restrictions were lifted on Brazil's foreign exchange
trading on Jan. 13, the Brazilian currency, the real, has
depreciated 32 percent against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, which has Latin America's largest economy, has been in
talks with the IMF over the release of the second installment of a
41.5 billion dollars international rescue package.
</P>
<P>
In December, Brazil received 9 billion U.S. dollars from the
IMF and used it to bolster its sagging currency reserves, now at
36 billion U.S. dollars, down from 74 billion dollars last July. A
second parcel might help restore the confidence of skittish
investors.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, Finance Minister Pedro Malan said that
the appointment of Fraga, ``one of Brazil's best economists,'' was
in line with the current direction of the country's economic
policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
