<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Reports New Clashes in No-fly Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. warplanes attacked
Iraqi air defense sites in both northern and southern no-fly zones
on Tuesday, U.S. Defense Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
Two incidents occurred in the northern no-fly zone when U.S.
pilots conducted their routine patrol, Pentagon spokesman Lt. Col
Steve Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
At 2:20 p.m. Iraqi time (1120 GMT), two U.S. F-15E strike
Eagles dropped two predision-guided bombs on an anti-aircraft
artillery battery in response to being targeted by Iraqi radar.
</P>
<P>
In a separate incident about 15 minutes later, U.S. aircraft
dropped bombs on another anti-aircraft artillery site, Campbell
said, adding details were sketchy and he could not provide the
location of the clashes.
</P>
<P>
"There was no damage to our aircraft and they are still
flying," he said.
</P>
<P>
Army Col. Richard Bridges, another Pentagon spokesman, said
there were two incidents in the southern no-fly zone at about 1
p.m. Iraqi time (1000 GMT) when U.S. fighter jets were illuminated
by Iraqi radar near the town of Basra.
</P>
<P>
"We fired at a missile site and an anti-aircraft artillery
radar," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
