<HEADLINE> Chinese Enterprises in Singapore Bound into Association </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese enterprises based in
Singapore Tuesday bound themselves into a society named "China
Enterprises Association (Singapore)" (CEA(S)) with an aim to
enhance business cooperation between China and Singapore and to
promote their businesses in the city state.
</P>
<P>
CEA(S), that has won approval by Singapore's Register of
Society, this afternoon held its first membership meeting with
participation of some 70 delegates from Chinese enterprises in
Singapore. At the meeting, the participants passed the CEA(S)'s
charter and elected Wang Lujun, president of COSCO (Singapore) Pte
Ltd., as first president of the association.
</P>
<P>
The charter stipulates that CEA(S)'s objects are to promote
business interest of Chinese enterprises in Singapore. To promote
business cooperation between China and Singapore and to promote
investment and joint venture with Singapore enterprises in
Singapore as well as in third country.
</P>
<P>
At a party held this evening to mark the occasion, Tang Guan
Seng, senior parliamentary secretary of the Ministry of Trade and
Industry of Singapore extended warm congratulation on the
establishment of CEA(S) and expressed his hope that CEA(S) will do
a good job in enhancing business relations between Singapore and
China.
</P>
<P>
China has some 200 state-owned and private enterprises based in
 Singapore and their businesses amount to some 40 percent of the
total 8.1 billion U.S. dollars in the trade volume between China
and Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
