<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Deals Signed Between Clans in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Abdalle Aroneh clansman, and
Eli-Omar clansmen loyal to Ali Mahdi Mohamed of the main Abgal
clan signed a four- point peace deal over their conflict on Monday
night in north Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Twenty delegates, 10 each, from the two sides attended the
signing ceremony at the engineering block of Jako and Rajo of
north Mogadishu. Prestigious elders from the two sides and Somali
elite and dozens of people from the affected neighboring clans
also witnessed the event.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to implement an immediate and effective
cease-fire beginning mid-day Tuesday, exchange the 24 war
prisoners (five from one side and 19 from the other side) caught
during the fighting and kept in the countryside Tuesday, open the
200-meter-long road linking Mogadishu to the coastal towns
northeast of the capital and settle all prior disputes between the
two sides, including the land ownership and grazing.
</P>
<P>
Another peace deal was also signed in Mogadishu Monday between
Sheikhal and Biyomal clansmen fighting in the town of Jamama of
Lower Jubba region, about 100 kilometers north of the port town of
Kismayu in south Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Ten delegates from the two clans signed a seven-point agreement
in reducing the animosity between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The agreed points included the opening of the roads to Mogadishu
and Kismayu, the separation of their militiamen and face-to-face
negotiations to be opened for settling their differences.
</P>
<P>
There has been no reports of fighting Tuesday at the front
lines between the two clansmen since the message of cease-fire was
especially distributed among the militia commanders through field
radios in their respective militia bases.
</P>
<P>
However,  preparation for more fighting continues in the same
region of Lower Jubba, as the Marehan and Majerten clans fighting
for control of Kismayu continue building up their militia forces
in Kismayu and its outskirts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
