<HEADLINE> Ukraine, U.S. to Boost Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The consensus was reached at the fifth regular conference of
the Ukraine-U.S. Security Committee, which was held recently at a
U.S. air force base in Florida.
</P>
<P>
The committee operates under the leadership of the Ukraine-U.S.
Joint Commission founded by Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma and
U.S. Vice President Al Gore in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The two sides plan to convert a war-game field in the Ukrainian
state of Lvovskaya into a training center for the implementation
of NATO's Partnership for Peace program launched in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The conference focused on the discussion of the schemes to
strengthen bilateral military technological cooperation. The
problems of communication and command related to Ukrainian
peacekeeping forces were among the topics of discussion.
</P>
<P>
Conference participants also discussed the special partnership
between Ukraine and the North Atlantic Organization Treaty (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The next conference is scheduled to be held in Ukraine in the
last quarter of this year. 
