<HEADLINE> NPC Committee Discusses Economic Goals (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liu Bin, a member of the NPC Education, Scientific, Cultural
and Health Care Committee, criticized the government's failure to
invest legally prescribed growth rates for education and
scientific research over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Li Yining, a member of the Financial and Economic Committee,
said government departments should correctly understand that
meaning of "active fiscal policy" does not only refer to spending
more, but also to "actively increasing government revenues."
</P>
<P>
He warned that local governments should avoid overspending in
order to avoid endangering the economic order.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the 7.8 percent economic growth rate for last year,
the State Statistics Bureau explained that China's GDP rose 7.2
percent in the first quarter of 1998, 6.8 percent in the second
quarter, 7.6 percent in the third quarter and nine percent in the
four quarter. The bureau noted that the annual growth rate reached
7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
This rising trend resulted from stronger government measures,
according to a bureau official.
</P>
<P>
The general principles for formulation of the national economic
plan and budget for this year include:
</P>
<P>
-- increasing domestic market demand as the major means for
promoting economic growth;
</P>
<P>
-- stabilizing agriculture and expanding industrial production
by deepening the reform of state-owned enterprises;
</P>
<P>
-- using all means possible to increase exports;
</P>
<P>
-- preventing and eliminating financial risk; and
</P>
<P>
-- maintaining sustained, rapid and healthy national economic
development. 
</P>
