<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Deepen Foreign Trade Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- China plans to adopt a series of
measures to deepen foreign trade reform, according to last
Wednesday's edition of the International Business Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC)
plans to relax the requirements for approving and granting foreign
trade rights to more enterprises, according to MOFTEC Minister Shi
Guangsheng.
</P>
<P>
Systems will be established for import-export management,
services offered by foreign trade agencies, information and
economic and legal macro-controls, said Shi.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC will continue sharp reductions in the volume of
licensed import and export commodities, said Shi.
</P>
<P>
Quotas will be allocated to exporters through public bidding,
according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC is currently drafting ruled governing bids for import
and tariff quotas, according to Vice-Minister Gao Hucheng.
</P>
<P>
Shi called for follow-up, feedback, readjustment and control
mechanisms to strengthen management and ensure the efficient use
of quotas. China encourages imports of machinery and electrical
products, especially new and high-tech products, as well as key
equipment. Shi added that this year's plans call for increase
imports of goods which will promote readjustments of the economic
and industrial structures.
</P>
<P>
He called on chambers of commerce to strengthen coordination
and service functions in an effort to safeguard the trade order
and better serve the interests of members, enterprises and society.
</P>
<P>
China welcomes more exhibitions which attract manufacturers
and foreign-funded enterprises engaged in the production of high
technology and brand name products, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
