<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Official Attends Meeting on POWs Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Deputy Prime
Minister and Defense Minister Salem Sabah Al-Salem Al-Sabah
Tuesday left for Geneva to attend a meeting on the issue of
Kuwaiti detainees in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A tripartite committee, which groups Kuwait, Iraq and the 1991
Gulf war allies, is due to meet on Wednesday and Thursday to
review the issue of Kuwaiti and other countries' prisoners of war
(POWs) captured by Iraqi troops during its occupation of Kuwait in
1990-1991, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said it will not take part in the Geneva meeting.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Salem, also head of the National
Committee for Missing and POWs, praised the role of the United
Nations Security Council members who recently decided to set up a
panel to assess Iraq's compliance with a international mandate
regarding the issue of Kuwaiti POWs.
</P>
<P>
These international efforts brought relief to the Kuwaitis,
Salem said.
</P>
<P>
A similar meeting scheduled for early January on the Kuwaiti
side of the border with Iraq was canceled because the Iraqis
refused to show up.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait insists that Iraq still holds more than 600 detainees of
Kuwait and other countries, an allegation that has been repeatedly
rejected by Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs remains one of the main stumbling blocks for
an improvement of relations between Kuwait and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
So far, other issues arising from the seven-month occupation,
namely the U.N.-mediated demarcation of the Iraqi-Kuwaiti border
and Iraq's compensation through U.N.-monitored Iraqi oil-sales,
have been solved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
