<HEADLINE> Zambian President in Congo (K) for Peace Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba is now in Kinshasa Tuesday in a fresh bid to end six
months of civil war in the Democratic Republic of Congo, a report
reaching here from the Congolese capital said.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba and Congolese President Laurent Kabila would discuss
peace talks to be held in Lusaka, Zambia in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
The talks, to involve foreign and defense ministers from the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) and those from
Burundi, Rwanda, Kenya, Libya and Uganda, are part of Chiluba's
plan to secure a cease-fire in the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Kinshasa residents turned out in force Tuesday, lining the
streets to welcome Chiluba with singing and dancing.
</P>
<P>
"I sense something important has been reached," Kabila's
cabinet director Abdoulaye Yerodia was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It seems something is coming up like the removal of the last
obstacle. And maybe soon one will be able to say peace has
returned," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba has spearheaded regional efforts to end the conflict
which erupted in Africa's third largest country on August 2 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kabila accuses Rwanda and Uganda, who helped him topple former
President Mobutu Sese Seko in May 1997, of fomenting the revolt
by ethnic Tutsis and other opponents.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Chad have all sent troops to
fight for Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda, who fell out with Kabila over how to ensure
security on their western borders, say their own security
concerns must be addressed first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
