<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commits Anti-Doping Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
committed on Tuesday its efforts in the fight against doping in
international sports.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered to the world conference on doping in
sports, European Culture Commissioner Marcelino Oreja said: "The
European Union is totally committed to combating doping."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said that the European council at the heads of
state and government level last December in Vienna had promised to
do whatever the 15-nation bloc could to stamp out this wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
The union promised to work hand in hand with the sporting
organizations in the fight against doping and Europe has a special
political reason for it.
</P>
<P>
Oreja said: "Europe is the birth-place of the Olympics and more
world championships and Olympic Games are held in Europe than
anywhere else. So Europe has almost a natural duty to lead the
way in this fight."
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the European Union,
suggested a three-phase combat against doping in sports among the
union member states and countries elsewhere. Its measures include
unified regulation, unified measure and strict enforcement.
</P>
<P>
It believes that to make the fight effective there has to be a
clear-cut definition of doping, a single list of banned substances
recognized by all sporting organizations, harmonized tests and a
harmonized system of penalties.
</P>
<P>
The European Union promised to study intensively the doping
problem after the world anti-doping conference and before May to
decide what concrete actions it can take to implement the
agreements made at the world anti-doping conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
