<HEADLINE> Russian Minister Vows to Fight Extremism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian Interior Minister Sergei
Stepashin vowed Tuesday to crack down on the radical-right Russian
National Unity (RNE) movement if its actions "go beyond the limits
of the law."
</P>
<P>
Several hundred members of the neo-Nazi movement, wearing black
uniforms and red armbands with a swastika-like symbol, staged a
march in northern Moscow on Sunday. Police detained some of the
marchers but soon released them, arguing that they had no formal
grounds for halting the march or arresting the participants
because the RNE was registered with city authorities.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin said a conference on Monday thoroughly discussed the
march, the latest in a series of incidents highlighting the rise
of political extremism, and some police chiefs have been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
"That march was illegal, and it was the duty of the police to
prevent it. I've issued an order, so they will hold no more
marches of this kind either in Moscow or in other cities,"
Stepashin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Russian Security Council will hold a special
session on measures to combat political and religious extremism.
</P>
<P>
The minister also urged the State Duma, or lower house of the
Russian parliament, to speed up the discussion of draft laws on
ways of combating extremism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
