<HEADLINE> Russian Prosecutor General Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prosecutor General Yuri
Skuratov resigned Tuesday for "health reasons," the Kremlin said.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin, who returned to the Kremlin for the
first time after checking out of the Central Clinical Hospital
Sunday, accepted his resignation and sent a letter to the
Federation Council, or the upper house of parliament, the
presidential press service said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has urged the council, which nominates prosecutor
generals, to free Skuratov from his duties immediately.
</P>
<P>
Skuratov's deputy, Yuri Chaika, told the Interfax news agency
that Skuratov was hospitalized after complaining of pains in the
area of his heart Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Yevgeny Lisov, head of the Chief Control Department of the
presidential administration, denied reports that Skuratov resigned
due to a conflict with the administration, saying his department
had a good relationship with the Prosecutor General's office.
</P>
<P>
Interfax said the Federation Council would consider Skuratov's
resignation on February 16.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the council said under the Russian Constitution,
"the prosecutor general is appointed and dismissed by the
Federation Council on the initiative of the president." 
</P>
