<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Observatory to Install Astronomical Telescope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Astronomical
Observatory (BAO) under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS)
plans to install an astronomical telescope with a diameter of four
meters at its Xinglong Station by the year 2004.
</P>
<P>
The Large Sky Area Multi-Object Fiber Spectroscopy Telescope (
LAMOST) will be the largest of its kinds in the world, according
to BAO Astronomer Su Hongjun.
</P>
<P>
LAMOST will have a focal distance of 20 meters and will be able
to observe 4,000 astronomical spectrum in a single night, far
above the average 600 observations for other telescopes of its
kind, said Su.
</P>
<P>
The telescope will have the capacity to observe stars which are
millions of times darker than those visible to the naked eye,
according to Su.
</P>
<P>
CAS Academicians Wang Shouguan and Su Dingqiang proposed the
LAMOST Project which was listed as one of the top-priority
scientific projects in 1996. The State Planning Commission
approved the undertaking of the project in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Su noted that the project is in the initial design stage. He
added that the telescope will improve the research of stars and
galaxies both inside and outside the Galaxy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
