<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strengthening Efforts to Protect Wetland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- China is strengthening wetland
protection by drafting new rules, said an official from the
National Administration of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
Today is set as the "World Wetland Day". Zhang Jianlong,
director of the department of the wilderness under the NAF, called
on the government to spare no efforts to protect wetlands in China,
which is facing continuing degeneration.
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted that China is formulating a plan of action
concerning wetlands protection, which will be submitted to the
State Council for approval by this mid-year. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NAF is also considering drafting a national
regulation on wetland conservation.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands, the natural ecological systems often referred to as
the earth's "kidneys", play an important role in water
conservation and the prevention of erosion and flooding.
</P>
<P>
China now has wetlands with acreage amounting to 65.7 million
ha. The NAF launched an investigation on current wetlands in
china, and the results are expected to be available by 2000.
</P>
<P>
In past years, the increasing population and economic
development have resulted in the continued deterioration of
wetlands in China, noted Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the NAF show that in the past forty years, the
country lost some two million ha of wetland or one half of the
acreage of the country's coastal wetlands.
</P>
<P>
Some experts even said heavy flooding along China's Yangtze,
Nenjiang and Songhua rivers last summer have been caused, at least
in part, by the continuing degeneration of the wetlands.
</P>
<P>
China signed the "Wetlands Convention of International
Importance, Especially in Waterfowl Habitats" in 1992. So far, it
has set up 148 natural reserves to protect the wetlands, covering
an area of 12.83 million ha.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
