<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak-U.S. Talks on Non-proliferation Remain Inconclusive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and the United
States ended their talks on issues of nuclear non-proliferation
and security here Tuesday with no specific results.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides agreed to hold further expert-level meetings on
export controls and strategic restraints in March and April," said
a joint statement issued after the talks held between Pakistan's
Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed and U.S. Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
The two countries considered further steps to advance the
objectives of the dialogue and agreed to remain in close touch
during the negotiations on Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty in the
Conference on Disarmament, according to the joint statement.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government reiterated its position on the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty enunciated by Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif in his address to the U.N. General Assembly in September
last year, that is Pakistan will sign the CTBT until all sanctions
against it are lifted.
</P>
<P>
This was the eighth round of talks on the issues of nuclear
non-proliferation and security between Pakistan and the United
States in eight months, which were held in a "positive and
constructive atmosphere", said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reviewed the security situation in South Asia
particularly in the context of the agenda of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. side expressed its "strong support" for the current
talks between Pakistan and India including on Kashmir, and the
Pakistani side urged the United States to play a more active role
towards the solution of the Kashmir dispute, according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that the next round of the dialogue will
be held before the middle of the year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, both Shamshad and Talbott were optimistic about the
process of dialogue. "During these eight rounds of talks we have
significantly achieved our objectives," said Shamshad during a
briefing at the Foreign Office.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign secretary declined to go into details
about what the two sides had achieved.
</P>
<P>
Talbott said on the occasion that "we covered full gamut of our
issues in the relationship. The United States and Pakistan have
many, many interests across of wide scope that we want to develop
and we have touched on a number of those here, too."
</P>
<P>
Talbott, who arrived here from New Delhi Monday afternoon, also
called on Prime Minister Sharif and held a meeting with Foreign
Minister Sartaj Aziz Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Talbott, Sharif emphasized Pakistan's
desire for "a durable peace and stability" in the region and the
role which the United States and the international community
should play for "an expeditious final settlement of the Jammu and
Kashmir dispute which lay at the center of security problems in
South Asia," said a press release by the Prime Minister's Office.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
