<HEADLINE> IOC Inquiry not Extended to Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee stated that the ad-hoc commission looking into
allegations of unethical behaviour by the IOC members would not
extend its inquiry to the Sydney bid for the 27th Olympic Summer
Games in 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release of the IOC, pursuant to the
recommendation of the ad-hoc commission, the IOC president Juan
Antonio Samaranch sent letters of inquiry on January 29 relating
to all past Olympic Games bidding cities for the 1996, 1998, 2000,
2002 and 2004 Olympic Games. A similar letter has been sent to
the 2006 Olympic bidding cities citing together with further
instructions on the bidding process. Sydney is expected to
respond to this letter, as are the other bidding cities, before
February 15.
</P>
<P>
Australian Olympic Committee John Coates disclosed last month
that he gave 35,000 U.S. dollars each to two African IOC members
on the eve of the IOC's voting for 2000 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The IOC said that no further official inquiry has been opened,
and no decision to open any inquiry on past bidding practices will
be taken until further information is received from the bidding
cities.
</P>
<P>
The IOC reiterated that the inquiry into the bidding practices
of Salt Lake City was based on specific facts and documents, not
rumors or unfounded allegations.
</P>
<P>
The investigation into the Salt Lake City bidding scandal has
led to resignation of four IOC members and five more suspended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
