<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Studies Duty-Free Cut-off Effect on Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
on Tuesday that it has initiated a study that will re-examine the
effects on employment when duty-free sales end on July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Seven years ago, the EU agreed unanimously to abolish duty-free
sales of tobacco and alcohol at EU ports and airports in mid-1999.
Such sales were seen as a blatant distortion within the bloc's
single market.
</P>
<P>
Abolishing duty-free sales will eliminate nearly 350,000
permanent jobs within the union, and see a loss in annual revenues
in the billions of euros.
</P>
<P>
The EU, harassed by high unemployment for the past decade, is
being challenged with the wisdom of abolishing the job-intensive
trade at a time when almost all union member states are striving
to increase employment.
</P>
<P>
European Union states such as Germany, France and Britain
recommended revising the duty-free cut-off decision during last
December's EU Summit in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
But any revisions need the unanimous agreement of the 15
finance and economy ministers from the member states to allow the
extension.
</P>
<P>
Denmark has been one of the outspoken critics of the revision
idea. It argues that an extension of duty-free sales after July 1
would damage the credibility of the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
