<HEADLINE> EU OKs Motorola's WIDs Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
on Tuesday that it has approved the entry of Motorola as a
shareholder of Symbian in producing an operating system for
wireless information devices (WIDs).
</P>
<P>
The approval means that Motorola can now join with its Symbian
partners in developing and producing the operating system.
</P>
<P>
Symbian is a joint venture created last August by European
mobile phone manufacturers Ericsson, Nokia and the hand-held
computer and operating system manufacturer Psion.
</P>
<P>
The aim of Ericsson, Nokia and Motorola, as manufacturers of
wireless information devices, and Psion, as a developer of this
technology, is to establish the EPOC operating system as a
standard for wireless information devices and to stimulate the
development of a mass market.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the watch-dog for fair competition within the
European Union (EU) market, has established that the entry by the
American mobile phone manufacturer into the WIDs cooperation does
not constitute an advantage against other manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
The commission also received a formal commitment from Symbian's
shareholders that the operating system will be licensed to third
parties on an open and non-discriminatory basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
