<HEADLINE> ADB Helps Nepal Improve Private Sector Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
recently approved two technical assistance grants totaling 300,000
U.S. dollars to help the Nepali government improve private sector
investment activities, the bank's Nepal Resident Mission said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The first technical assistance is for improving accountability
and corporate governance in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
"The main objective of the assistance is to improve information
disclosures and good corporate governance in order to restore
investor confidence required for sound and sustainable private
sector development," the mission said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The assistance, which is expected to commence in February, will
be implemented over a period of two months, the press release
said.
</P>
<P>
The second technical assistance aims to improve financial
sector regulation and governance in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
"The main objective of the assistance is to assist the
government in developing a proper regulatory system for financial
governance for the non-bank financial segment of the financial
sector," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the assistance will also start in February and be
implemented over a period of four months. 
</P>
