<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Legal Cooperation Proceeds Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and U.S. anti-drug
commissioners are currently working in exchange positions on the
embassy level in line with an agreement signed by the two
governments.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yang, president of China's Supreme People's Court,
announced the exchange agreement prior to his meeting with Anthony
Kennedy, associate justice of the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
He noted the establishment of a regular exchange mechanism
involving two Sino-U.S. joint groups in charge of law enforcement
and legal exchanges.
</P>
<P>
"The ministries of foreign affairs, justice and public security,
as well as judicial and procuratorial departments are
participating in the groups," said Xiao.
</P>
<P>
He said law enforcement group from the two countries are
coordinating the campaign against international crime, drug
trafficking, gun smuggling, terrorism and violent crimes. The
second group is responsible for reciprocal visits, exchanges of
materials and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
Xiao briefed Kennedy on China's efforts to govern the country
according to law and build a socialist country based on the rule
of law.
</P>
<P>
Kennedy has visited China four time in seven years, and noted
that he has gained a better understanding of China with each visit.
He specifically pointed to "the changes in the way Chinese people
approach the law." He also pointed to the "rapid and extensive
development in China's legal construction," and noted that the
country has "proceeded in an exemplary manner."
</P>
<P>
The two chief judges also exchanged views on legal aid and
continuing education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
