<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Hits Vietnam's Northern and Southern Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's northern and southern
provinces were hit by drought, Vietnam's English daily "the Saigon
Times Daily" reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Drought has gripped through northern provinces, leaving some
1.3 million people thirsty for water and threatening vast paddy
areas, said the daily.
</P>
<P>
The Water and Irrigation Management Department of Vietnam's
Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development said 360,000
hectares of 2.5 million hectares of winter-spring paddy in
northern Vietnam would likely to be parched.
</P>
<P>
If the water level of the Red River falls by 2.0 meters, but
irrigation canals are not dredged now to reserve water, the
on-going drought will impose more serious impacts, according to
the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Some provinces have planned to use 30 percent to 50 percent of
more than 160,000 hectares of winter-spring paddy likely to be
destroyed by the drought for cultivating short-term cassava, sweet
potatoes, beans, peanuts or sugarcane.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Mekong Delta is also in the same boat, said the
daily, with more than 200,000 hectares of paddy lacking fresh
water and invaded by seawater, including 100,000 hectares in Kien
Giang Province, 55,000 hectares in Soc Trang Province and 49,000
hectares in Tra Vinh Province.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development said
local authorities had developed water sources and called for the
public to use water more economically, dig water wells and build
rain water reservoirs. If the situation gets worse, people can be
evacuated from affected areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
