<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses U.S., Britain of Obstructing Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Health Ministry on
Tuesday accused the U.S. and British representatives in the
U.N. Sanctions Committee of blocking the approval of two important
health contracts concluded under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed source in the ministry told the Iraqi News Agency
that one contract is related to purchasing an apparatus called
Arjon Lazer that can be used to treat diseases of retina.
</P>
<P>
This contract was suspended by the U.S. and British
representatives under the pretext that the apparatus was of dual
military use, said the source.
</P>
<P>
The source added that the apparatus was of limited capacity
less than two watts and could not be used for other purposes, and
that Iraq had imported such kind of apparatuses in the 1980s and
they were used by physicians to save patients from blindness.
</P>
<P>
The other contract that was suspended by U.S. representatives
is related to an apparatus called "Laser Exaimar" that can be
operated by lazer radiation and ultraviolet ray to treat diseases
such as short-sightedness, far-sightedness and astigmatism.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. representative put this contract on hold under the
pretext that some of its components could be used in tests of
missiles, said the source, adding that such kind of apparatus
could only be used for medical purposes.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been suffering from shortages of medicine and medical
appliances due to the over eight-year U.N. sanctions imposed on
the country following its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal, now under its fifth phase, allows Iraq
to export limited amount of oil to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 22 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
