<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan, Japan Shine Fourth Day of Winter Asiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YONGPYONG, South Korea, February 2 (Xinhua) -- It was the
Kazakhstan and Japan's turn to shine in the Kangwon Winter Asiad
on Tuesday when they split the four gold medals of the fourth day
of the games, with South Korea and China content with just silvers
or bronzes after their medals haul in previous competitions.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan, who won all cross country competitions except women'
s relay at the last edition of the Games in Harbin, China, in 1996,
took the gold medal in the men's cross country 4x10 kilometers
relay on the Rainbow Snow Course in Yongpyong, while Japan claimed
the other gold on the skiing in the men's giant slalom.
</P>
<P>
The close rivals also played even in the Outdoor Ice Rink in
Chunchon where Kazakhstan pocketed the gold in the men's speed
skating 5,000 meters race and Japan won the women's 3,000m today.
</P>
<P>
Both Japan and Kazakhstan grab three golds, trailing behind
medals leader South Korea, with eight golds atop in the medal
standings, and China at the second place with six golds.
</P>
<P>
However, China, who would not be content to be also-ran after
significant performances of their short track skaters in the first
three-day competitions, opened the day with a record-breaking
victory from veteran Xue Ruihong, who topped the first round
competition in the women's 500m race with a time of 39.290 seconds,
a time bettering the Asian record.
</P>
<P>
"It was Xue's fastest time after the 1994 Winter Olympics,"
said Hu Chunfang, manager of the Chinese speed skating team. "She
has the gold in her pocket could she skate like today on Wednesday.
"
</P>
<P>
Xue finished fourth in the same event in the Lillihammer
Olympics in 1996 and won a World Cup in the following year.
</P>
<P>
Her teammate Yang Chunyuan was second in 40.610 while Japan's
Yumiko Osuga was third in 40.840.
</P>
<P>
Radik Bikchantayev of Kazakhstan dented Japan's dream of
defending its men's 5,000m speed skating title, winning in a time
of 7:16.46, with South Korean Jun Moon taking silver in 7:17.97
and Japanese Kazuki Sawaguchi third, 7:17.29.
</P>
<P>
Bikchantayev, who skated in the last pair of six with Park Jae-
man of South Korea, took the advantage of the missing of Japan's
Shigekazu Nemotoin, who beat him in Harbin in 1996, to the final
victory.
</P>
<P>
Led by Vladimir Smirnov, who took the first gold for Kazakhstan
in the men's 15km cross country classic on Sunday, a Kazakhstan
quartet, included Pavel Ryabinin, Andrey Nevzorov and Igor
Zzubrilin, led the whole way to the finish line of the men's 4x10
km relay in one hour 41 minutes and 12.8 seconds. Japan and South
Korea finished second and third respectively.
</P>
<P>
Japan's first gold Tuesday came from women's 3,000m speed
skating when Aki Narita beat her country fellow Yuri Horikawa to
second and Song Li of China, who took the bronze.
</P>
<P>
Join Kawaguchi was Japan's hero Tuesday as he outclassed three
South Koreans to win the men's giant slalom gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Kawaguchi, 24, who was silver medalist of the Super-G slalom
Sunday, revenged his loss to beat Hur Seung-woo of South Korea to
capture the title with a combined time of 2:35.40. Hur took the
silver with his teammates Lee Ki-Hyun and Choi Moon-sung following
in turn.
</P>
<P>
Strong winds blew after the first round in the morning when
Kawaguchi led the herb with a time of 1:21.64, giving the Japanese
a chance to vault to a winning time of 1:13.76 in the second round
three hours later.
</P>
<P>
Hur finished first in the second round in 1:13.02 but the time
was not enough to beat the winning gap of the leading Japanese
after the Korean only skated to 1:22.95 in the first round.
</P>
<P>
At the ice hockey rink, Japan celebrated for its women's team
edging over Kazakhstan 2-1, while men's defending champion
Kazakhstan trounced South Korea 12-1 in its first group match
before roaring host fans at Kangnung Indoor Ice Rink.  
</P>
</TEXT>
