<HEADLINE> North China's Hebei Province Gets New Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Niu Maosheng was elected
here as governor of north China's Hebei Province at the third
session of the Ninth Hebei Provincial People's Congress held today.
</P>
<P>
The 60-year-old Niu, a native of Beijing, is of Manchu
background and a senior engineer. He previously served as Chinese
minister of water resources and also appointed as deputy governor
and later acting governor of Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Niu graduated in 1963 from the Beijing Institute of
Agricultural Mechanization as a farmland irrigation major. He
served as a technician with the Beijing Municipal Bureau of
Hydraulic Engineering, the Party secretary of the Beijing's Miyun
County Committee, section chief and deputy bureau chief of the
Beijing Municipal Bureau of Water Resources and Meteorology, and
general manager of the China Water Resources Development
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Niu has worked in the field of water conservancy for a long
time, serving in the 1980s successively as director of the Yellow
River Management Committee, vice minister of Water Resources and
secretary general of the State Flood Control Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
He also served as deputy head of the State Flood and Drought
Control Headquarters, and head of the Leading Group of the Project
for Diverting South Water to the North.
</P>
<P>
Niu was appointed as deputy governor and acting governor of
Hebei Province on Nov. 6, 1998 at the 5th meeting of the Standing
Committee of the 9th Hebei Provincial People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
He was member of the 8th National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) and was elected
a member of 15th Central Committee of the Communist Party of
China (CPC), 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
