<HEADLINE> Prominent Egyptian Writer Dies at 75 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 2 (Xinhua) -- A prominent Egyptian writer and
newspaper editor died of cancer Tuesday in Cairo at the age of 75,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Fathi Ghanem was hospitalized two weeks ago. Surgery and
chemotherapy have failed to prevent the tumor from spreading from
his colon to his liver and other organs.
</P>
<P>
Ghanem was a state prosecutor before taking up the career in
journalism. He wrote many famous novels which were made into
movies and television films.
</P>
<P>
"The Man Who Lost his Shadow" and "Zeinab and the Throne" are
among his most well-known novels, both of which have been turned
into television series.
</P>
<P>
Born in Cairo on March 24, l924, Ghanem supported the late
Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser in his 1952 revolution,
which toppled the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
He was the board chairman of the country's Middle East News
Agency in 1965-1966 and editor-in-chief of a number of state
newspapers including the Al-Gomhuria daily. In l973-1977, he was
the editor-in-chief of the weekly Rosa al-Youssef.
</P>
<P>
From 1977 on, he wrote novels, commentaries, articles on arts
and politics for several other Egyptian and Arab newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Ghanem was a member of Egypt's Supreme Cultural Council and
several literary awards winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
