<HEADLINE> Ninth NPC Adopts 21 Laws (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The National People's Congress
(NPC) Standing Committee, China's top legislative body, has
enacted and revised 21 laws since March last year, according to a
senior legislator.
</P>
<P>
The NPC has adopted a series of measures to accelerate the
country's legislative process and improve the quality of new laws,
said Jiang Chunyun, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the comments at a symposium attended by jurists,
professors and legal researchers.
</P>
<P>
Important legislation included laws governing securities,
forestry, land management, the organization of village committees,
higher education, foreign exchange and military service, according
to Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Seven draft laws are currently under discussion, including the
Contract Law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ninth NPC Adopts 21 Laws (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee, under the leadership of Li Peng,
has introduced a mechanism requiring at least three hearings prior
to the adoption of a law. "The mechanism allows sufficient time
for debate," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
The long list of new measures includes:
</P>
<P>
-- Publishing draft laws of public interest prior to adoption
in order to solicit opinions and ensure that new legislation
reflects the true will of the people;
</P>
<P>
-- Strengthening legislative surveys and research, with high-
ranking legislators, including the chairman, conducting fact-
finding tours to solicit opinions on legislative items; and
</P>
<P>
-- Defining the duties and responsibilities of special NPC
committees.
</P>
<P>
As part of an effort to realize its goal of "preliminarily
establishing a socialist legal system with Chinese characteristics,
" the NPC has drawn up a five-year plan which includes adopting 89
new laws, such as the laws on legislation, supervision and
property rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
