<HEADLINE>   Malaysia's Sailor Sets Sail for Round-the-World Voyage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's sailor Azhar
Mansor Tuesday set sail in a non-stop solo voyage around the world.
</P>
<P>
He became the first Malaysian to circumnavigate the globe in a
wind-powered yacht "Jalur Gemilang" (shining stripes) named after
the national flag.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad flagged off the
historic record attempt by Azhar Mansor at Awana Porto Malai in
Pulau Langkawi resort island, northern Malaysia, according to the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said on the occasion that Azhar's effort would be
tough as he had to sail round the world in less than 105 days
without any stop.
</P>
<P>
This was the third challenge to bring glory to the country made
by Malaysians after the failures of the conquest of Mount Everest
and the North Pole Expedition, Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Azhar, who will be 41 on February 11, is attempting to set two
world records -- the first non-stop solo circumnavigation of the
world on a new west-east route verified by the World Sailing Speed
Record Council United Kingdom, and the fastest non-stop solo world
circumnavigation for 15m/18m yacht.
</P>
<P>
With 20 years' experience as a sailor, Azhar has received the
letter of authorization from the World Sailing Speed Record
Council for the trip.
</P>
<P>
Azhar has prepared two-and-half years for this trip including
charting his route.
</P>
<P>
He is known as the first yachtsman to begin the challenge of
going around the world from the Indian Ocean with other
challengers started off from the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
He has taken along with him two tons of canned food for the 100
to 130-day voyage.
</P>
<P>
The sailor plans to return to Langkawi sometime in May this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surveys Show Public Concern About Hygiene in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The public are concerned with
the cleanliness and hygiene conditions in Hong Kong, in particular
the littering problem.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the key findings revealed in the first two of a
series of 10 opinion surveys commissioned by the Steering
Committee on Healthy Living of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The surveys, conducted by the Social Sciences Research Center
of the University of Hong Kong in mid-December and mid-January,
aim to gauge the attitude and behavioral patterns of Hong Kong
people on hygiene practices and standards and the overall
cleanliness of the city.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,600 respondents were asked during the two surveys
to assess the cleanliness of Hong Kong by using a scale of zero to
10. The benchmark findings show a rating of 5.2 on the overall
cleanliness of the local environment.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the survey findings Tuesday, Deputy Secretary for
Health and Welfare Robin Gill said the results confirmed the
rationale for the government to launch the Healthy Living Campaign
which aims to instill healthy life-style concepts in the community
through the promotion of healthy habits, proper hygiene practices
and environmental improvement.
</P>
<P>
"To make Hong Kong a cleaner and more healthy city is the joint
responsibility of the government and the public at large," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that with the active support and participation of the
community, we will together make Hong Kong a cleaner and healthier
home for every one," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
