<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of East Asia Continues Expansion Despite Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Bank of East Asia
(BEA) Tuesday announced a consolidated profit after a tax of 928
million HK dollars (118.97 million U.S. dollars) for the year
ending December 31, 1998, a decrease of 55.5 percent over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Announcing its final results for the year 1998, the BEA, the
largest independent Chinese bank in Hong Kong, said earnings per
share decreased to 0.68 HK dollars (0.087 U.S. dollars) from 1.56
HK dollars (0.2 U.S. dollars) for the year 1997.
</P>
<P>
Operating profit before provisions fell by 2.7 percent to 2.645
billion HK dollars (339.1 million U.S. dollars), while operating
income declined slightly by 1.1 percent to 4.345 billion HK
dollars (557.05 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The directors of the bank recommended payment of a final
dividend of 0.14 HK dollars (0.018 U.S. dollars) per share which,
together with the interim dividend of 0.18 HK dollars (0.023 U.S.
dollars) per share paid in September 1998, constituted a total
dividend per share of 0.32 HK dollars (0.41 U.S. dollars) for the
year. The combined dividend represented a decrease of 55.9 percent
over the total dividend per share paid for the year 1997.
</P>
<P>
Noting that 1998 was exceptionally difficult for the whole
banking industry in Hong Kong, BEA Chairman and Chief Executive
David Li stressed that the underlying performance of the bank had
been very positive during the year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the weak business environment, Li said, the bank
enjoyed a 3-percent increase in net interest income. This was the
result of careful management of interest rates for both loans and
deposits, Li explained.
</P>
<P>
The bank also controlled its costs very effectively, with
operating expenses rising only 1.4 percent, Li said. Most of all,
the bank achieved a very healthy level of profit before taking
provisions into account, just 2.7 percent below the record level
of 1997, Li added.
</P>
<P>
Li attributed the decline in profits to two main causes:
weakening demand for loans and an increase in specific provisions
for bad debts.
</P>
<P>
Despite the temporary difficulties in the economic environment,
BEA continued to develop its business in 1998, in line with its
longer-term strategy, Li continued.
</P>
<P>
It opened seven new retail outlets in Hong Kong, bringing the
group's local network to a total of 105 outlets.
</P>
<P>
In China's mainland, BEA opened a new representative office in
Chongqing and became one of just two overseas banks with
permission to conduct Renminbi business in both Shanghai and
Shenzhen. Expansion also continued overseas, with a fifth branch
opening in Canada.
</P>
<P>
While the bank will continue its expansion, 1999 will be
another difficult year, said Li. "We will continue to exercise
prudence in all aspects of our business and place special emphasis
on such areas as costs, customer service and training."
</P>
<P>
In both Hong Kong and the mainland, he said, the bank would
endeavor to broaden its income sources by offering more high value-
added products and services and by placing greater emphasis on non-
interest income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
