<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
shed more than half a percent Tuesday, dragged down by investors
taking profits after Monday's record-breaking close.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index slipped 16.7 points to
2907.0, down from a record 2923.7 point close Monday.
</P>
<P>
On the Australian equities market, the all industrials index
dropped 30.6 points to 5289.2, while the all resources index off
loaded 5.1 to 941.2 points.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks also succumbed to profit taking, with the
industry sub-index slumping 52.9 points to 6669.5.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank shed 19.4 cents to 26.68 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia slipped 28.1 cents to
23.869 Australian dollars and Westpac bank fell 27 cents to 11.00
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank gained ground, adding 10 cents to 10.60 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resource major BHP retreated 17.7 cents to 11.44 Australian
dollars, while fellow diversified miner Rio Tinto eased 5.6 cents
to 19.244 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Firmer precious metal prices helped the gold index rally 11.3
points to 1079.5.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney Tuesday afternoon
closed at 288.90 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared to Monday's
close of 287.45 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 482.48 million shares traded for 866.72
million U.S. dollars, with 675 stocks falling, 557 stocks rising
and 420 stocks steady. 
</P>
