<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Industry Output Keeps Going Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The lingering financial turmoil
continued to hit the manufacturing sector of the Philippines with
the volume of production down 24.4 percent for November 1998 from
November 1997, the National Statistics Office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The value of production for November 1998 dropped by 18.1
percent from its previous year's level, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The value of net sales also dropped by 10.7 percent and its
corresponding volume by 16.1 percent from a year earlier, it said.
</P>
<P>
The drop in production was largely attributed to the declines
in petroleum products, food manufacturing, electrical machinery,
and transport equipment, the office said.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, gainers in both value and volume of
production were the paper and paper products, rubber products,
textile, and wood and wood products sectors.
</P>
<P>
On capacity utilization, the ratio of output to the maximum
rated capacity of a plant, the statistics showed that 38.1 percent
of the firms were operating below 70 percent capacity in November
1998, compared to 29.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On a positive note, 18.3 percent of the sample firms operated
at full capacity as against 17.8 percent the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
