<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Are Against Fortune Telling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Scientific boffins in China
have called for a new campaign to crack down on superstitious
activities and persuade the public from going to fortune tellers.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent social survey conducted by the China
Association for Science and Technology (CAST), 35.5 percent of the
people questioned now believe in fortune telling, compared with 28.
7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The experts say the development of a market economy has given
Chinese people many opportunities but has increased their stress
levels because of fierce competition. They say that people's
cultural and scientific awareness must be improved to cater to
their sense of spiritual barrenness.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that the better educated the public, the
less they believe in fortune telling. And it seems that the
majority of the people are against superstitious activities such
as geomancy, palm reading and analyzing the components of a
written Chinese character to forecast one's future.
</P>
<P>
A CAST official, in charge of the survey, said that China
should increase people's scientific awareness, and ban the
publication of books and magazines disseminating superstition.
Those who make money by telling fortunes should be punished
according to the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Immunization Day Observed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Tuesday observed the
second round of the 5th national immunization day (NID) in a bid
to make the country polio-free by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
Under the 2nd round of the NID, about 20 million children in
the country aged 0-5 were given oral polio vaccine (OPV).
</P>
<P>
As many as 120,000 vaccination centers, including the mobile
ones at the railway stations and bus terminals, were set up to
conduct the OPV program across the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the third and fourth NIDs were not successful, the health
authorities would launch more NIDs in the future to make the
country really polio-free, Health Secretary M.M. Reza was quoted
by press reports as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the first round of the 5th NID was observed on
December 14 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The budget of the 5th NID has been estimated at over 300
million taka (6.2 million U.S. dollars), which is being jointly
financed by Japan, the Bangladeshi government and other
international agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
