<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes Take off from Turkey for Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. warplanes Tuesday took off
from the Incirlik Air Base in Adana, southern Turkey, for
northern Iraq, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ten F-15 fighter jets, six F-16s, two Prowlers planes, four
tanker aircraft, one AWACS plane and four commander planes took
off from the Incirlik base at hours between 10:00 a.m. and 11:15
a.m. local time (08:00 and 09:15 GMT) to patrol the no-fly zone
in northern Iraq, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
U.S. bombardments of Iraqi sites in the no-fly zones have
become commonplace recently after the four days of U.S.-British
air strikes against Iraq in mid-December last year.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its western allies imposed two no-fly
zones in northern and southern Iraq after the 1991 Gulf War to
protect the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south
from alleged Iraqi regime's suppression.
</P>
<P>
There are 45 warplanes of the allied forces stationed in
Incirlik as part of the Operation Northern Watch to patrol the
northern no-fly zone in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
