<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Continue Cultivating Oil Palm Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Primary
Industries Minister Lim Keny Yaik said Tuesday that his country
would continue to seek suitable places abroad to cultivate oil
palm to ensure a steady supply of palm oil in anticipation of
increasing global demand.
</P>
<P>
The global demand for palm oil is predicted to reach 24 million
tons by the year 2005 and further to 44 million tons by the year
2020.
</P>
<P>
Palm Oil Research Institute of Malaysia has conducted studies
in Latin America and West Africa which are believed to have the
potential and environment for oil palm cultivation, the minister
said here.
</P>
<P>
Local entrepreneurs are encouraged to go abroad, especially in
the countries of these two regions, for long-term palm oil
production, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has embarked on joint ventures in oil palm plantations
with other producing countries to help boost palm oil production
for increasing world consumption.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is one of the leading palm oil producers with its
production amounting to 9.05 million tons in 1997. 
</P>
