<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Army Hospital Overflows With Corpses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The mortuary at the Army Base
Hospital in Lagos is filled with corpses of Nigerian soldiers of
the West African peace- keeping force of ECOMOG killed in the
war-torn country of Sierra Leone, The Post Express newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted sources at the hospital as revealing that "the
place is overflowing with dead bodies".
</P>
<P>
Many of the corpses were seen at the hospital lying in
hurriedly-made coffins and they were covered with the national
flag just behind the pathology department inside a room referred
to as the "engine room", according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Wounded soldiers littered the eight-block ECOMOG Ward which can
no longer accommodate fresh intakes and the hospital authorities
have converted the pediatrics department into an extension of the
ECOMOG Ward, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
A wounded soldier told the paper that in Freetown, capital of
Sierra Leone, especially within the ECOMOG camp at the Lungi
International Airport, there is a large army of wounded soldiers
waiting to be ferried back to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The soldier who pleaded anonymity added that when he was
brought back on January 22, it was difficult to secure even a
standing space inside the aircraft because of the high casualty
rate of soldiers waiting to be brought back home.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "on January 22 when we returned, 20 corpses
accompanied us while over 30 returned a week earlier."  
</P>
</TEXT>
