<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Secures Loan From Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday secured a
loan of 300 million U.S. dollars from Japan as part of its
requested 5 billion dollars under Japan's Miyazawa initiative of
30 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 300 million dollar untied loan was provided by Export
Import Bank of Japan (JEXIM) to Malaysia's Industry Bank.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Second Finance Minister Mustapa Mohamed signed here
Tuesday a letter of guarantee for the loan on behalf of the
government.
</P>
<P>
The loan initially negotiated in May last year was incorporated
into the Miyazawa initiative, a financial stimulus package aimed
at helping battered Asian economies recover from the current
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mustapa told a press conference after the signing that during
the informal summit of East Asian leaders in Hanoi in December
last year, Japan pledged 1.5 billion dollars in assistance to
Malaysia, of which 500 million dollars were under JEXIM.
</P>
<P>
He said another 200 million dollars could come in another two
to three months' time while the remaining 1 billion dollars
pledged will be channeled through Japan's Overseas Economic
Cooperation Fund.
</P>
<P>
Mustapa said the loan is not tied to any particular conditions
like goods or services that have to be bought from Japan or
contracts that have to be awarded to Japanese companies.
</P>
<P>
The loan would be used by Industry Bank and its subsidiary,
Exim Bank of Malaysia Bhd, to meet their financing requirements in
supporting the industrial sectors and the promotion of exports
respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
Half of the 10-year loan will be denominated in the yen while
the balance will be in U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
