<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Takes Biggest Step to Save Sport from Doping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee took the biggest step in its 106-year history to save
sport from doping with the opening of the World Conference on
Doping in Sport here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which opened amid the Salt Lake City 2002
Winter Olympics bidding scandal, will deal with four themes:
protection of athletes, prevention of doping, the legal aspects
and financial consideration. The goal of the conference is to
establish and adopt effective measures against doping to be
implemented by all in the world of sport and in collaboration with
government organisations.
</P>
<P>
In his addressing to the opening of the conference, the IOC
president Juan Antonio Samaranch admitted that the IOC has been
confronted with a serious situation over the past few weeks with
regard to allegations of wrongdoing leveled against some of its
members.
</P>
<P>
"We have taken all the necessary measures and are continuing
our investigations to ensure that Olympic ethics are respected,"
said the president.
</P>
<P>
The Salt Lake City bidding scandal, the biggest threat to the
Olympic movement in its history, has led to the resignations of
four IOC members with five more suspended.
</P>
<P>
By firing members accused of breaking rules on taking gifts or
cash from Salt Lake City before the city won the right for the
2002 Olympic Winter Games, Samaranch is now trying to re-establish
the credit and confidence of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
The president said at the conference, "The International
Olympic Committee was the first to recognize the threat of doping,
and in 1968 it established a Medical Commission."
</P>
<P>
He promised that the IOC will seek to adopt concrete measures
for combating doping at all levels of sport.
</P>
<P>
"We want to send a clear message to athletes, governing bodies
and organising committees that we are committed to doping all we
can to eradicate doping, which is poisoning the world of sport,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
One of the key aims of the conference is to establish an anti-
doping agency, which would oversee the global fight against drugs
in sport. It would be comprised of representatives from the
Olympic movement, governments, medical and scientific community
and athletes.
</P>
<P>
Chair of the Working group responsible for the formation of the
agency, Canadian lawyer Richard Pound, said "We believe that a
single, international body will make a significant contribution to
combating doping in sports. The agency will also be responsible
for overseeing and enforcing a code of ethics for doping in sport.
"
</P>
<P>
The conference will also seek to agree on a clear definition of
doping, a single Medical Code and list of banned substances, a
code of ethics regarding doping and a program to improve
communication about the dangers of using drugs.
</P>
<P>
The conference is attended by more than 500 delegates,
including IOC officials, head of national Olympic Committees,
heads of international sports federations and athletes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
