<HEADLINE> China to Expand Overseas Contracting, Labor Service Sector (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ministry said it will enhance the management and
supervision of relevant companies and projects, and establish a
quality control and guarantee system for contracted projects.
</P>
<P>
Initiated in the late 1970s, China's project contracting and
labor service sector has been growing quite rapidly over the past
20 years.
</P>
<P>
China signed 11.773 billion U.S. dollars worth of overseas
contracts last year involved in engineering, labor services,
design and consultancy, a 3.7 percent increase over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The turnover soared 20.9 percent in 1998 to a record 10.13
billion US dollars, bringing the cumulative total to 58.37 billion
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
By November 1998, Chinese companies had signed overseas deals
in these fields worth 81.72 billion US dollar, with the turnover
reaching 56.66 billion US dollars, and a total of 1.75 million
workers sent abroad.
</P>
<P>
Shi Guangsheng, minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, commented that the activities MOFTEC was focusing on
had huge market potential but as yet China has only secured a tiny
share of it.
</P>
<P>
"Last year, global construction investment totaled 3,200
billion US dollars, but China's involvement only accounted for one
to two percent of the world's contracting market and one percent
of labor flow, so there is still enormous room to expand," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
