<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Sailor Sets Sail for World Voyage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's sailor Azhar
Mansor Tuesday set sail in a non-stop solo voyage around the
world.
</P>
<P>
He became the first Malaysian to circumnavigate the globe in a
wind-powered yacht "Jalur Gemilang" (shining stripes) named after
the national flag.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad flagged off the
historic record attempt by Azhar Mansor at Awana Porto Malai in
Pulau Langkawi resort island, northern Malaysia, according to the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said on the occasion that Azhar's effort would be
tough as he has to sail around the world in less than 105 days
without any stop.
</P>
<P>
This is the third challenge made by Malaysians, after the
conquest of Mount Everest and the North Pole Expedition, to bring
glory to the country, Mahathir noted.
</P>
<P>
Azhar, who will be 41 on February 11, is attempting to set two
world records -- the first non-stop solo circumnavigation of the
world on a new west-east route verified by the World Sailing Speed
Record Council United Kingdom and the fastest non-stop solo world
circumnavigation for 15m/18m yacht.
</P>
<P>
With 20 years' experience in the sea, Azhar has received a
letter of authorization from the World Sailing Speed Record
Council for the trip.
</P>
<P>
Azhar had prepared for two and half years for this trip
including charting his route.
</P>
<P>
He is known as the first yachtsman to begin the challenge of
going around the world from the Indian Ocean compared with others
who started off from the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
He has taken along with him two tons of canned food for the
100- to 130-day voyage.
</P>
<P>
The sailor plans to return to Langkawi sometime in May this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
