<HEADLINE> Inflation to Go Up in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's inflation is likely to
shoot up further in the early part of this year from the 30.6
percent recorded last December, Standard Chartered Bank has said.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Zambian Financial Mail quoted the Business Trends, a
publication by Standard Chartered Bank, as saying the continued
depreciation of the Zambian currency and increase in food prices
is likely to further push up the inflation.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year inflation recorded at 30.6 percent rose from
27.6 percent the previous month. Business Trends attributed the
increase to weak capital inflows the country experienced last year
and the balance of payment difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult to see what government can do now to slow
inflation, since the real money is already falling, thereby adding
to the already inflationary pressures at work in the economy,"
said Business Trends.
</P>
<P>
According to the publication, the government is reluctant to
see interest rates driven much higher, knowing that such
development would further intensify the cash flow and liquidity
problems of many firms.
</P>
<P>
The longer the trend will continue, the stronger would be the
upward pressure on interest rates, the publication said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0150 </DOCNO>
