<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Falling in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices moved lower in Tokyo
Tuesday for the second straight day on market concern that rising
long-term interest rates could dampen the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 115.35 points, or 0.80
percent, from Monday's close to end at 14,349.83.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First section issues, dropped 5.64 points or 0.50 percent to 1,113.
73.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went slightly up to an estimated
314.40 million shares from Monday's 310.78 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Izutsuya, a major regional department store based in Kitakyushu,
southern Japan, was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
A remark by Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa that he
will leave interest rates to be decided by the market for the time
being stirred bond selling, as investors took it to mean he does
not attach importance to the rise in long-term interest rates,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar's fall against the yen also stirred stock
selling, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 679 to 459, with 162 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
