<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Bank Ready to Intervene in Money Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia (BI), the
country's central bank, said here Tuesday that it is ready to
intervene in an effort to calm down the money market.
</P>
<P>
"BI is ready to intervene in the market, for how much it
takes," BI governor Sjahril Sabirin said.
</P>
<P>
Since October last year, BI has been continuing its
intervention in the money market by injecting 5 million to 10
million U.S. dollars every day. The value of the rupiah, the local
currency, against the U.S. dollar had been kept at 7,000 to 8,000
rupiah per dollar between October to December last year.
</P>
<P>
However, it dropped to 9,000 rupiah per dollar in mid-January
because of the outbreak of monetary crisis in Brazil and the
unstable political situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last month, Sabirin said, the government would
make efforts to keep the exchange rate of the rupiah below 7,000
per dollar.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah closed slightly firmer at 8,900 against the
greenback in very thin trading on Monday as share prices fell
nearly 1 percent due to a lack of fresh leads in the local market.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the monetary crisis in Southeast Asian
countries in July 1997, the value of the rupiah has lost more than
60 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin said that if the rupiah strengthens, intervention will
only be limited to between 1 million and 5 million dollars a day.
</P>
<P>
He said the key factor in the recovery of the rupiah is the
final discussion on three draft political laws and clearer
information on banking recapitalization.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's House of Representatives on January 28 passed three
political bills concerning the June general election, which were
described as progress in political reform in the country.
</P>
<P>
To overcome the prolonged economic crisis, the government has
decided to finalize the recapitalization of more than 70 troubled
banks in the country by June this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
