<HEADLINE> S. Leone to Strengthen Military Ties with Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- A high-powered Sierra Leonean
military delegation is due in Nigeria Tuesday in a bid to
strengthen military cooperation between the two countries, media
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The 14-member delegation led by Sierra leonean Chief of Defence
Brig-Gen. Maxwell Khobe is expected to consolidate renewed talks
on military cooperation initiated last week by a Nigerian
delegation.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian delegation signed with Sierra Leone a
comprehensive Memorandum of Understanding which emphasized the
need to train the armed forces of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Acting Director of Defence Information Lieutenant Col. Sam
Tella said Monday in Lagos that the delegation would visit various
military training institutions including Command and Staff
College, Nigeria Defence Academy and Nigerian Army Depot.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will be divided into three groups to visit the
army, navy and air force respectively during its seven-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Under the Status of Forces Agreement signed in 1997 between the
two countries, Nigeria was given powers to train the Army of
Sierra Leone, and develop its Navy and Air force.
</P>
<P>
Brig-Gen. Khobe, until his appointment as Sierra Leone's Chief
of Defence Staff, was the Commander of the West African
peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG in Sierra Leone, which
recaptured Freetown from Major Johnny Koroma-led government.
</P>
<P>
The reinstated Tejan Kabbah government faced fresh crisis last
month when rebels loyal to the Revolutionary United Front launched
attacks on capital Freetown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
