<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Call Rates Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korean call rates Tuesday
fell to the 5-percent range Tuesday, the record low in the country,
showing the government's determination to hold down overnight
rates among financial institutions, said the Bank of Korea (BOK).
</P>
<P>
Call rate stood at 5.98 percent at five p.m. Tuesday and the
yields on three-year state bonds were also down 0.09 percentage
points from Monday's 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, three-year corporate bonds posted yields of 8.12
percent, down 0.01 percentage point.
</P>
<P>
Observers attributed the fall of call rates to the government's
move to cut rates.
</P>
<P>
Monday, the central bank said its monetary policy for 1999 will
focus on lowering market interest rates further in a bid to boost
the economy and stabilize the won-dollar exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to cut our repurchase rate further to help bring the
overnight call rate down," BOK Governor Chon Chol-hwan said at a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
Call rates, which banks charge to each other for overnight
lending, hovered around 13.1 percent in October 1997, surged to 31.
3 percent in December 1997, when the worst financial crisis in 50
years hit the nation. And then it gradually declined to 6.00
percent as of last Saturday after the government took measures to
recover the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
