<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Extend Losses on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Share prices extended its
losses on Singapore Stock Market Tuesday as continued sales
brought more pressure on key index stocks.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) dropped 20.28 points
and ended at 1,386.59 points, the lowest level in nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
The total volume was increased marginally to 177.88 million
units valued at 288.38 million Singapore dollars (about 170.94
million U.S. dollars). Falls outnumbered rises by 173 to 64 with
185 shares unchanged.
</P>
<P>
ST Engg remained the top favorite of the day on a turnover of
13.4 million shares. The second largest block was the 8.37 million
stock parcel by CK Tang w99 that transacted at 0.185 Singapore
dollars per share. LKN w99 was next with a volume of 6.89 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Venture led gainers of the day with a 35-cent rise to finish at
7.7 Singapore dollars. It was followed by Venture w99 that edged
up 30 cents to close at 6.4 Singapore dollars. DBS F and SPH
inched up 20 cents and ended at 13 and 19.4 Singapore dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, multimedia peripherals maker Creative 50
continued to lead top losers of the day, falling 250 cents to
close at 20 Singapore dollars. NatElec was next with a drop of 42
cents to end at 4.78 Singapore dollars. OCBC sank 30 cents and
closed at 11.3 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said news that government-linked conglomerate SemCorp
Industries Ltd. was taking an extraordinary write-down of 419.5
million Singapore dollars as part of its restructuring sparked
selling in the second half of Tuesday's trading session.
</P>
<P>
The company was quoted as saying it was also divesting some of
its major business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
