<HEADLINE> Nigerian Soldiers to Return to Barracks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian soldiers are all to be
moved into the barracks within one month to prepare ground for the
impending civilian governance, Commander of the Nigerian Army
Corps of Artillery Maj-Gen. Abdul-One Mohammed was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said on Monday in Ogun State that the plan of the Head of
State General Abdulsalam Abubakar to cede power to civilians in
May had necessitated a schedule of activities in the military
including the movement of soldiers to barracks this month, The
Guardian newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that General Abubakar would keep faith with his pledge
to hand over power on May 29 this year and the army was inclined
to stick to its constitutionally assigned role by being
continuously loyal to Nigeria and its people.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper New Nigerian reported Tuesday that army
headquarters in Lagos had directed soldiers serving in the Lagos
State anti-crime outfit " Operation Sweep" be reduced by 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
A circular to that effect had been issued to the headquarters
of the team and gradual withdrawal of military men from the team
would commence this month.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement is in line with presidential directive that
military participation in various organs assisting the police to
maintain law and order be phased out to prepare for overall
withdrawal of military persons from civil organs.
</P>
<P>
The military coordinator of "Operation Sweep", Lt. Col. Kenneth
Minimah, confirmed receiving such directive to reduce army
strength by 50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
