<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Trio Ready for Historic Desert Trek </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Three veteran Canadian
adventurers will soon launch their much-awaited attempt to cross
the Empty Quarter of Arabia, the world's largest sand desert, the
Dhabi-based Khaleej Times reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The trio, to kick off their grueling expedition from Oman, will
pass through Saudi Arabia and end their two-month-long journey in
the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
With the help of three native Bedouins and 12 camels, the Jamie
and Leigh Clarke brothers together with Bruce Kirkby plan to set
out from Salalah, Oman, this week in a bid to become the first
Westerners in more than 50 years to make a foot crossing of the
Empty Quarter, or the Rub Al Khali.
</P>
<P>
They will try to retrace the route taken by British explorer
Wilfred Thesiger, the last Westerner to complete the crossing in
1947.
</P>
<P>
Wilfred was the first and the only person to have navigated the
treacherous eastern section of the Empty Quarter, which is
largely in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
During the journey, the trio is expected to face numerous
challenges, notably the Uruq Al Shaiba, a mountainous range of
towering dunes hundreds of miles long.
</P>
<P>
They will also have to skirt the famous quicksand of Umm Al
Samim, or Mother of Poison.
</P>
<P>
Jamie, 30, a former cross-country ski champion of Canada,
successfully scaled the summit of the Mt Everest in 1997. His
brother Leigh, a lawyer and adventurer, and Bruce Kirkby, an
engineer-turned wilderness guide, will produce a film on the
expedition stretching over 1,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The 300,000-square-kilometer Empty Quarter has more sand, both
in surface and volume, than any others on earth.
</P>
<P>
The world's best known desert, the Sahara, constitutes just 10
percent sand with the remainder being made up of rocks, scrub and
mountainous terrain, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
