<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Both the leftwing and rightwing parties of France have
criticized the refusal by the French Senate to approve the law on
guaranteeing equal access to political posts by men and women. The
call for the holding of a referendum on the issue, which must be
agreed upon by President Jacques Chirac, is on the rise, as a
referendum can approve the law without the Senate.
</P>
<P>
-- The political scenery of Israel is atomized as nine new
political parties have come up to compete in May for the seats in
the parliament, where 11 parties already exist. Since 1996,
Israelis vote to elect members of parliament and prime minister at
the same time. It is enough to be elected to parliament with only
1.5 percent of the suffrages.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The merger of two great banks, to be made through the
launching of buying of shares of Paribas bank by the Societe
Generale at a record cost of 15.1 billion euros (17 billion U.S.
dollars) in France, will produce the world's fourth largest
banking group after Bank America and CitiGroup of the United
States, and Hong Kong Shanghai Banking Corp of Britain.
</P>
<P>
-- Between 1976 and 1983, the leaders of four military juntas
of Argentina systematically kidnapped the children of political
prisoners. For the past 15 years, the grand-mothers of these
children have been looking for their traces with obstinacy. An
association of these grand-mothers said nearly 400 children had
been kidnapped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
