<HEADLINE> Cambodia's King Sihanouk Considers Successor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's King Norodom
Sihanouk is considering his successor, opposition party leader Sam
Rainsy disclosed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rainsy, president of his self-named party, told reporters at a
press conference held at his party headquarters that he had an
audience with the King on Monday at the royal palace for nearly
three hours.
</P>
<P>
He said he and the king had discussed many topics including a
successor to the throne.
</P>
<P>
The king revealed that his successor may be his son Prince
Norodom Sihamoni or his wife Queen Norodom Monieath, Sihamoni's
mother, according to Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
But he said there are also some other possible candidates
including Prince Norodom Ranariddh, another of his sons and
president of the National Assembly, and Prince Norodom Sirivudh,
the king's half-brother who has just returned home from three
years of exile abroad.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitutions, the king's successor would be chosen
by a royal council and from among the king's sons or members of
the main branches of Cambodia's royal family. Although Prince
Ranariddh is the king's eldest son, he would not automatically
take the throne.
</P>
<P>
So if Queen Monieath is to be the king, the constitution would
be amended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
