<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Calls Good Talks With U.S. on Non-Proliferation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and the United
States Tuesday concluded their eighth round of official talks on
the issues of nuclear non-proliferation and security with positive
comments from both sides.
</P>
<P>
"We have had a detailed session and we have had good
discussion, characteristic of the tradition of frankness and
cordiality that we have established over the past seven rounds of
talks," Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed told the media
after his talks with visiting U.S. Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad said Pakistan and the United States have held eight
rounds of talks on the concerned issues in the past eight months.
</P>
<P>
"That itself indicates the seriousness and intensity of our
engagement and this engagement, I am sure, has been for a purpose,
and that purpose has been bringing our position and our respective
concerns and objectives closer," he said.
</P>
<P>
"During these eight rounds of talks, we have significantly
achieved our objectives," Shamshad said. However, the foreign
secretary did not go into the details about what the two sides had
decided, only saying a joint statement will be issued after
Talbott's meetings with Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz and
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on whether the United State had got any
commitment from Pakistan on signing the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty (CTBT) and deweaponization, Talbott said Prime Minister
Sharif made a commitment on the CTBT at the United Nations in
September last year. "It has always been on the agenda," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We covered full gamut of our issues in the
relationship. The U.S. and Pakistan have many, many interests
across of wide scope that we want to develop and we have touched
on a number of those here, too."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden, Talbott
declined to comment, only saying, "It was a regional issue."
</P>
<P>
Talbott arrived here Monday afternoon from New Delhi where he
held the eighth round of talks with Indian officials on nuclear
non-proliferation issues, which ended Sunday with an agreement to
meet again, but no sign of any substantive breakthrough was seen.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation led by Talbott included officials from the
National Security Council, the Department of Defense and the
Treasury Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
