<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Intensifies Anti-Drug Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam uncovered more than 2,330
drug-related crimes in the two months since Vietnamese Prime
Minister Phan Van Khai initiated a national drive against drug
abuse and trafficking last November, Vietnam News Agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the two months prior to the drive, the number of
uncovered cases increased by twofold.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 4,505 offenders were arrested and more than seven
kilograms of heroin, 67 kilograms of opium and 30,000 doses of
narcotics were confiscated in the first two months of the drive,
which will last until the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The number of arrests increased by 1.8 times and the volume of
confiscated drug almost tripled compared with the previous two
months.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Vietnam's police arrested 18,700 offenders who were
involved in trafficking and stockpiling drugs and organizing drug
abuse. They confiscated 56.53 kilograms of heroin, 1,135 kilograms
of opium and 379 kilograms of marijuana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
