<HEADLINE> "Five Principles" Are Common Ground, Says Lithuanian Politician </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Lithuanian Parliament
Chairman Vytautas Landsbergis said today that he considered he had
found common ground for developing ties with faraway China: the
Five Principles for Peaceful Co-existence.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that his Baltic nation adopted a foreign policy
"similar with the 'five principles'."
</P>
<P>
It was Landsbergis' first China visit following his election as
chairman of the parliament. During his Beijing stay, he met with
Li Peng, chairman of the National People's Congress Standing
Committee, Vice Premier Qian Qichen and Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan. "I told the Chinese leaders of our willingness to develop
bilateral cooperation in all fields and the response was very
positive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although geographically far apart from each other, he insisted
that distance was not a barrier for the two countries to enhance
cooperation partially thanks to modern transport and telecom
convenience. "And there is hardly any point mentioning that we
have no political barriers or disagreements," he added.
</P>
<P>
This musician turned politician was also ambitious to play, as
he said, high notes in state-to-state politics. "The bilateral
exchanges should not be confined to reciprocal visits. I hope
future cooperation can bear more tangible results after my visit,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He was delighted that "a certain consensus" had been achieved.
"I and the Chinese leaders all considered that our two countries
have potential to tap in transportation, investment, tourism and
cultural areas of exchange. I will take back these messages in a
bid to encourage our government to speed up their pace of activity
and interaction with China," he said.
</P>
<P>
On inter-parliamentary exchanges, he said the contacts could be
expanded to the level of special committees inside the law-making
bodies besides the mutual visits paid by official parliamentary
delegations.
</P>
<P>
The former pianist was deeply impressed by the extent of China'
s cultural heritage after visiting such gems as the Forbidden City.
"I also saw the gigantic construction site in the downtown areas,
obviously an indicator of a healthy and developing economy," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
