<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Tea Production Hits All-Time Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenya tea output in 1998 hit a
record high of 294.17 million kg, an increase of 33.27 percent
over the previous year, according to statistics released Tuesday
by the Tea Board of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The board, which regulates the operations of the tea industry
in Kenya, attributed the output increase to the plenty of water
brought by heavy rains last year and efforts by farmers to apply
required inputs as well as enhanced processing factory capacity.
</P>
<P>
A report by the African Tea Broker (ATB) based in Mombasa shows
 increased tea output in major tea producing countries in 1998.
India registered 629.17 million kg of tea, with Kenya ranking the
second followed by Sri Lanka, 280 million kg.
</P>
<P>
According to official data, Kenya tea output was 220.72 million
kg in 1997 when the crop was badly hit by drought, 257 million kg
in 1996 and 209 million kg in1995.
</P>
<P>
But the ATB and other industry sources said forecast of a
drought in the first half of 1999 meant that the performance in
1998 could not be repeated.
</P>
<P>
Tea growing areas in Kenya have reported limited rains since
early last December. Kenya's Meteorological Department said
drought has something to do with the La Nina weather phenomenon,
which often follows the El Nino.
</P>
<P>
Tea is Kenya's leading foreign exchange earner ahead of
tourism, coffee and horticulture. Kenya is the world's leading
exporter of black tea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opens Travel Agency Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Five foreign travel agencies
have formally filed applications for setting up joint venture
travel agencies in China, following the government's go ahead for
an increase in such activities in a bid to open up the sector.
</P>
<P>
Increasing numbers of overseas travel agencies have expressed
their interest in such ventures after the "Interim Rules Governing
the Establishment of Sino-Overseas Travel Agencies" were
introduced on a trial basis last December, Wei Xiao'an, a
spokesman for China National Tourism Administration (CNTA), said
here today.
</P>
<P>
It represents a further step in China's opening up policy after
overseas travel agencies were first allowed to set up joint
ventures on a trial basis in the country's 12 national holiday
resorts in 1992.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, although many foreign travel agencies had
expressed their wish to enter into the China market, they were
quite cautious because of the lack of regulations governing such
activities," Wei said.
</P>
<P>
To date, according to him, only one Sino-Swiss travel agency
been given permission to set up a joint venture in the Dianchi
Lake Holiday Resort in Kunming, capital of Yunnan Province in
southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Wei declared that the new policy will be conducive to
accelerating the internationalization of China's tourism industry,
to using the international sales network to help expand China's
inward bound tourism figures, and to improving the quality of
China's own travel agencies.
</P>
<P>
Wei acknowledged that it may aggravate competition in the
country's travel sector, warning that perhaps the expansion should
be introduced in a gradual manner.
</P>
<P>
"The current proposals are to allow only one such joint venture
travel agency for each of the provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Explaining why the interim rules do not allow the joint venture
travel agencies to be engaged in the outbound market, Wei said
that at present only 67 Chinese travel agencies have approval to
handle outbound tours, plus 300-odd businesses serving as tour
agents.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, for those domestic agencies without such permission,
it seems unfair to give such rights to joint ventures. Besides,
there are also some technical considerations." added Wei, who is
also director of CNTA's Policy and Law Department.
</P>
<P>
Wei added that in an effort to improve the quality of travel
agencies, the government's watchdogs revoked the business licenses
of over 1,500 unqualified travel agencies in 1995. And the
following three years saw a similar ruling applied to an average
of over 400 travel agencies annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quality and Market Diversification Key to China's Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- China has vowed to raise the
quality of export commodities and develop a diversified foreign
trade market this year, according to Shi Guangsheng, the minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
China is to export more high-tech, high value-added and further
processed industrial finished goods this year, Shi said a recent
national conference on foreign trade and economic cooperation, the
International Business Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Exports of machinery and electronic products, especially
complete sets of equipment and high-tech products, are extremely
important, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, primary industrial finished goods make up the bulk
of China's exports.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, Shi also stressed that the export of
namebrand commodities should be encouraged as well as expanding
the variety of goods available.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he reiterated that China should develop a
diversified market for foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Markets in Africa, Latin-America, East Europe and the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) have great potential, he
said and urged entrepreneurs to find appropriate ways of
exploiting the trade in those regions by developing efficient
marketing strategies.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the traditional markets that China has
developed in the United States, Japan and Europe to be
strengthened, saying that efforts to expand them should be
intensified.
</P>
<P>
A focus on quality and a strategy to diversify the markets
should be given some importance when considering overseas
investment for China, including agreeing contracts for foreign
projects and services, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
