<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Sets Rules on Coffee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- No miller or individual in
Kenya will be allowed to market coffee on behalf of farmers,
except the Coffee Board of Kenya, Agriculture Minister Musalia
Mudavadi said in a Kenya Gazette Supplement, the East African
Standard newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has finally gazetted tough rules
governing the operations of the coffee industry in line with
recommendations made by a task force appointed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the gazette supplement dated January 29, Mudavadi said that
no person is allowed to market coffee unless licensed by CBK under
the Coffee Act.
</P>
<P>
The rules also re-affirm the established tradition in the
country where coffee is sold from a central auction. Sale of
coffee by private treaty, as demanded by some stakeholders, has
been rejected.
</P>
<P>
The new rules also say that the government will confiscate
coffee sold directly to millers without going through an
authorized agent.
</P>
<P>
Licenses of such a farmer should be revoked or suspended and
notice to the effect publicized, the minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
