<HEADLINE> China Welcomes UN Decision to Establish Iraqi Evaluation Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said here today that China welcomes the
recent decision by the UN Security Council to establish three
evaluation groups concerning the Iraqi issue, describing it a
progress in breaking through the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
The Council has agreed upon the formation of three separate
groups to evaluate the disarmament of Iraq, the living condition
of its people, and the repatriation of Kuwaiti prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
With the decision, the spokesman pointed out at a routine news
conference this afternoon that the following key issue is to
guarantee the three groups would conduct an objective and just
evaluation over the Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, she stressed, the UN Security Council should tighten
its political guidance over the evaluation groups.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that the UN secretary-general would play an active
role in the evaluation work, and calls on all parties concerned to
show their sincerity so as to push forward the comprehensive
implementation of relevant UN resolutions with a just and
cooperative attitude, she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Peace in Mindanao Still Far Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Guns are now silent in Mindanao
and both President Joseph Estrada and Muslim rebel leader Hashim
Salamat have expressed their willingness to achieve peace in the
area, however a lasting peace in the southern Philippines remains
elusive.
</P>
<P>
During the past week, heavy fighting between government troops
and Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels has left more than
 30 people dead, dozens of others wounded and thousands of
civilians homeless.
</P>
<P>
However, neither side has admitted violation of a cease-fire
reached by the rebel group and the Ramos administration in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, the two warring parties signed a new cease-fire
and agreed to start formal peace negotiations on February 8. A
cease-fire, although shaky, is holding in Mindanao, despite some
isolated incidents of gunfights, according to the government.
</P>
<P>
Although the government declared that war is over in Mindanao
and the situation there is under control, observers believe new
fighting could easily erupt again before obstacles are removed to
a lasting peace in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The biggest obstacle to striking an accord on peace in Mindanao
is the demand of the rebel group for an independent Islamic state
there, which the government described as non-negotiable.
</P>
<P>
For more than 20 years, the 12,000-strong MILF, a break-away
group of the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF), has been
fighting for an Islamic republic in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
When the Ramos administration and the MNLF signed a peace
accord to end a 30-year-old civil war in Mindanao in September
1996, the MILF rejected the document and vowed to achieve its
objective by force.
</P>
<P>
So far, the MILF has not changed its separatist aims -- the
founding of a new, independent Islamic republic and recognition of
its sovereignty over 46 places in Mindanao, where it maintains its
own military camps.
</P>
<P>
But such a demand will not be accepted by the government.
President Estrada said Monday that he would like to meet MILF
Chairman Hashim Salamat to discuss peace in Mindanao, but the
territorial integrity must be excluded from their discussions.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, so long as the rebel group sticks to its demand for
an independent state in Mindanao, peace talks cannot produce any
concrete results, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Another obstacle to peace in the south lies in the difference
between the two sides in identifying the main problem in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The government has considered poverty as the root cause of
insurgency in Mindanao and promised more investments in the region
in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, MILF leader Salamat said: "Our concern is to be
free from oppression. We desire full opportunity to truly build
our culture, our own religion, our own way of life."
</P>
<P>
He suggested that studying the problem from a Muslim's point of
view might help the government find peace in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
But as the government regards the MILF's concern as
secessionist, no compromise could be made.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the MILF has accused the United States of instigating
the conflict in Mindanao, saying Washington had orchestrated the
recent fighting there to justify the approval of a proposed
Visiting Force Agreement (VFT) between the U.S. and Philippine
governments.
</P>
<P>
When fighting broke out last week, the Philippine Senate was
deliberating on the VFT which would enable the two countries to
resume large-scale joint military exercises.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has a vested interest in the Philippines,
particularly in Mindanao," a senior MILF official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Although the MILF cannot produce any evidence to back up the
allegation, the accusation reflected the complicatedness of the
Mindanao problem.
</P>
<P>
As their differences over the Mindanao issue cannot be easily
overcome, both the government and the MILF have to make greater
efforts to push the peace process forward, observers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
