<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills13 in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- At least 13 people have died of
cholera in Zambia since the disease broke out last month.
</P>
<P>
Lusaka City Council spokesman Daniel M'soka has confirmed
Tuesday morning in a telephone interview that out of 68 cases
recorded between January 11 to 31 in the city, five had died, 22
remain hospitalized while the rest have been treated and
discharged.
</P>
<P>
In Ndola, capital of Copperbelt Province in north Zambia, the
death toll has reached eight and 18 new patients were admitted to
the hospital between Sunday night and Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Cholera is a 100 percent killer disease which can be compared
to an atomic bomb and therefore there is need for everybody to
take precautionary measures," M'soka said.
</P>
<P>
He has appealed to people with relatives who have died of
cholera to bury their dead as quickly as possible to prevent the
disease spreading. 
</P>
