<HEADLINE> Ugandan President to Meet MPs on Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The meeting is scheduled to take place at his home in Mbarara
District in southwestern Uganda, the New Vision paper said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kagole Kivumbi, the public relations officer in the
Parliament, told Xinhua in a telephone interview Tuesday morning
that two committee chairmen had received invitations to meet the
president, but refused to confirm whether the talk is on or not.
</P>
<P>
The president passed the information to the clerk of the
Parliament who will notify the particular MPs, he added.
</P>
<P>
Isaac Musumba who chairs the committee on national economy and
Benedict Mutyaba who heads that of natural resources are expected
to brief the president on their committees' position on the
proposed dam at the tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
Nile Independent Power (NIP), a joint venture between AES of
Arlington Virginia and Madhvani International SA, plans to
construct a 250-MW hydro- electric generating plant on River Nile
about 10 km from the Owen Falls dams.
</P>
<P>
However, some MPs are contesting certain provisions in the
agreement, threatening to block the approval of the power purchase
agreement under which Uganda Electricity Board (UEB) must buy NIP
power.
</P>
<P>
The legislators want a comprehensive law in place before the
construction work begins.
</P>
<P>
They argue that the project will rip the country of colossal
amount of money. UEB must bear the responsibility to make monthly
payments whether or not it is able to re-sell all the electricity
generated by the project.
</P>
<P>
It also takes the risk of the water level decrease in Lake
Victoria, which will make the tariffs shoot up.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists and traditionalists are also against
construction of dams, saying that the dams would destroy the
famous Bujagali Falls and the cultural sites there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
