<HEADLINE> Denmark Pledges to Help Clear Land Mines in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Denmark pledged to help Vietnam
fund a long-term project to clear millions of unexploded land
mines scattered around its former demilitarized zone Quang Tri
Province, Vietnam's English daily Vietnam News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Danish-funded project in the central war-torn province will
pave the way for bilateral long-term charitable cooperation
between the two countries, Danish Foreign Minister Niels Helveg
Petersen was quoted as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
he was cutting the ribbon to officially launch a 1.1 million
U.S.- dollar project to remove unexploded mines and ordnance to
recover land for agriculture in Quang Tri's Gio Linh district.
</P>
<P>
The money, a non-refundable aid from the Danish government,
will be transferred to Vietnam through the Danish Environment
Fund.
</P>
<P>
In the first year of the project, the work will be carried out
on 120 hectares of land. The Quang Tri Provincial People's
Committee in collaboration with the Mine Advisory Group, a British
non-governmental organization, will be responsible for the
implementation of the project.
</P>
<P>
The Danish foreign minister has been in Vietnam since January
29 for a week-long visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
