<HEADLINE> Bureaucracy Causes100,000 Families Starving in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Bureaucratic bungling within the
Ministry of Local Government and National Housing has delayed the
processing of grain loan applications, leaving at least 100,000
families in Darwin District on the brink of starvation, the daily
Herald reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 hunger-stricken families applied for maize
under the grain loan scheme last August, but misunderstandings
between the district and provincial offices of the ministry have
seen the application forms being shuffled between the two offices.
</P>
<P>
Last week the disgruntled villagers told Border Gezi, Governor
of Mashonaland Central, that they were now surviving on wild
fruits, tubers and roots. Some villagers are surviving on relish
and tree leaves.
</P>
<P>
"I know there are misunderstandings between the personalities
in the two offices and that problem has resulted in my people
suffering. I am taking up the processing of the applications
personally and I promise that maize will have been delivered to
starving villagers soon," Gezi said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
