<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investments in Malaysia's Manufacturing Sector Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Proposed total capital
investments in Malaysia's manufacturing sector in 1998 fell by
44.5 percent compared to 1997, according to an official report
released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed total capital investments fell to 18.9761 billion
ringgit (about 4.993 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998 from 34.177
billion ringgit (about 8.993 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997,
according to the report on the performance of the manufacturing
sector in 1998 released by International Trade and Industry
Minister Rafidah Aziz at a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
In terms of number, applications for manufacturing projects
received in 1998 totaled 729 compared to 849 in 1997, registering
a decrease of 14.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Rafidah said foreign investments as a whole remained
encouraging in the year under review as applications with foreign
participation registered an increase to 507 from 494 in 1997,
constituting 69.5 percent of the total number of applications and
foreign investments totaled 12.6512 billion ringgit (about 3.329
billion U.S. dollars), accounting for 66.7 percent of the total
proposed capital investments.
</P>
<P>
The total foreign investments were only 12 percent lower than
1997. The significant drop in total proposed capital investments
were mainly attributed to the substantial decline in domestic
investments which fell sharply by 68 percent to 6.3249 billion
ringgit (about 1.664 billion U.S. dollars) from 19.7941 billion
ringgit (about 5.208 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997 given the
adverse effects of the economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The top five sources of foreign investments for 1998 were the
United States, Japan, Netherlands, Singapore and United Kingdom,
together accounting for about 80 percent of total foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, a total of 844 projects were granted approval compared
to 759 in 1997, reflecting an increase of 11.2 percent, with
approved investments increasing by 2.3 percent to 26.5056 billion
ringgit (about 6.975 billion U.S. dollars) from 25.82 billion
ringgit (about 6.794 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, she said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments in approved projects increased by 14
percent to 13.0828 billion ringgit (about 3.442 billion U.S.
dollars) while domestic investments fell by 7.1 percent to 13.3228
billion ringgit (about 3.506 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Rafidah Aziz said despite the difficult economic conditions,
the Malaysian manufacturing sector had shown continued resilience
and a creditable, though lower performance in terms of overall
investments and output growth.
</P>
<P>
But the minister did not reveal the output growth figures for
the sector for the whole year of 1998, only saying output in the
sector declined marginally by 1.4 percent in the third quarter of
1998 compared to the sharper contraction of 13.2 percent in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government, which recently liberalized
the equity policy for the manufacturing sector, will continue to
undertake various measures to bolster investor confidence and
carry out aggressive investment promotion efforts to key target
countries and regions such the United States, Japan and Australia.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for the manufacturing sector, which has provided
the main impetus to the growth of the country's economy, should
continue to be encouraging in 1999, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
