<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Lamas Learning More About Outside World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- UNESCO officials found it hard to
believe that Nyima Cering, a lama at the Johkang Temple in Lhasa,
capita of the Tibetan Autonomous Region, could speak English so
well when he described the history of Tibetan Buddhism to them.
</P>
<P>
His lucid explanation made the basics of Tibetan Buddhism
clearer to the U.N. officials.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old lama has to recite a lot of Buddhist scriptures
and has to pray every day, but he still finds time to study
English and classical Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"Languages are important tools for communication with the
outside world," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was recommended by the monastery to take part in a journey
sponsored by the Buddhist Association of China last November and
traveled by plane to Wutaishan Mountain in Shanxi Province, to
Lingyin Temple in Hangzhou, capital of Zhejiang Province, and to
Badachu in western Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said he enjoyed the chance to learn more about the outside
world and to exchange ideas with people in other parts of China.
"Only by learning about the outside world can I serve Buddha
better," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ngagwang lama, 38, shares the same view. He said he likes
raising flowers and watching TV, in addition to studying the
scriptures and praying, and especially likes watching Brazilian
football.
</P>
<P>
He has been at the Zhebung Monastery, 20 km west of Lhasa, for
16 years. There are five pots of flowers in his 8-square-meter
room and pictures of the 12 football teams of the 1998 World Cup
on his walls.
</P>
<P>
The 650 lamas at the 600-year-old monastery have an enjoyable
life, he said, and great changes have taken place in their lives.
Many of them have radios, tape recorders, calculators, calendar
watches, or popular sports shoes.
</P>
<P>
In the past, it was very difficult for lamas to know anything
about the outside world because of financial problems and a lack
of communications. It took three months to travel from Lhasa to
Beijing in the 1950s. Now it takes only one day by plane.
</P>
<P>
Lamas now cook their food with liquefied gas or in a solar
energy-powered kitchen. There are telephones and air-conditioners
in their houses, and, in addition to reciting scriptures and
praying they can learn about the outside world through newspapers
or TV.
</P>
<P>
Ali, 19, has a different hobby. He prefers studying English,
listening to popular music and playing computer games in addition
to studying mathematics and Chinese. His dream is to travel around
the world and make a contribution to the spread of Tibetan
Buddhism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hope Project Helps Poor Students Return To School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, February 2 (Xinhua) -- For many times, Song Guangzhou,
the teenage son of a Red Army soldier in Yan'an in northwest China'
s Shaanxi Province, stood by the school gate, enviously watching
other children of his age go to class. He could not do so because
of financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
However, he has now become a top student at the Hope School in
the village of Xinyaoze, thanks to the Project Hope, which started
in 1990 to raise money for pupils who had dropped out of school in
poverty-stricken areas of China.
</P>
<P>
Yan'an is one of China's poor revolutionary bases. Its 1.8
million people had a per capita income of 1,300 yuan (159 U.S.
dollars) in 1998. It has received 54 million yuan worth of
donations and built 220 schools since 1990, helping about 13,000
young people return to school.
</P>
<P>
According to Yao Jinjiang, who is in charge of the city's
Project Hope, the Hope School in Wenhuagou Village was the first
in the province. It was established in 1993 with 700,000 yuan
donated by central government employees, including President Jiang
Zemin and Li Peng, Chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
In the past six years, the people of Longgang District in the
Shenzhen Special Economic Zone in Guangdong province have donated
8 million yuan for 33 schools in Yan'an and some students in Japan
donated 60,000 yuan to the village of Muya for a Hope school that
made it possible for more than 70 pupils to have better classrooms.
</P>
<P>
The older generation in Yan'an have also tried to help the
younger generation. One man, 70-year-old Tian Shenggui, has
donated 2,700 yuan in the past couple of years, and local people
have donated more than 6 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The schools'teaching quality has also improved, according to
the Yan'an Hope School' Principal Dai Chengdong.
</P>
<P>
But, there is still a long way to go, says Yao Jinjiang,
because 50,000 sq.m. of school buildings are still needed in the
city and nearly 10,000 school dropouts need help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
