<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shaanxi to Open Four Tourist Spots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi
Province will build four parks featuring places of historical
sites in the Zhou, Qin, Han and Tang dynasties, provincial
governor Cheng Andong announced here recently.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi, whose capital Xi'an served as the capital of 13
ancient dynasties, has a great number of historical remains on or
under the ground surface.
</P>
<P>
A project on top of the agenda will be the construction of
exhibition halls separately containing terra cotta horses and
chariots and articles unearthed from the tomb of Qin Shihuang, the
first man to unite China. He founded the Qin Dynasty and assumed
the name "Shihuang", a Chinese word meaning first emperor. The new
exhibition halls will be near the Museum of the Terra Cotta Horses
and Warriors.
</P>
<P>
A park featuring the culture of the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-24 A.
D.) will be built at a place 10 km north of Xi'an, the provincial
capital. Archeological diggings show the place has a large
underground graveyard containing numerous cultural relics of high
artistic value.
</P>
<P>
The other two parks will be built in Baoji City, known as the
hometown of bronze ware, and in the northeastern part of Xi'an,
where are the ruins of the Daming Palace in the Tang Dynasty (618-
907).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
