<HEADLINE> 54 People Killed on New Zealand Roads in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 2 (Xinhua) -- January marked the worst
start to a
year on New Zealand roads this decade.
</P>
<P>
The Land Transport Safety Authority (LTSA) of New Zealand said

Tuesday in a release that 54 people were killed on the country's
roads
last month, making it the worst January road toll recorded since
1990,
when the same number died. The monthly toll was 11 higher than
January
1998, when 43 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very disappointing start to the new year,
particularly we
started the year announcing a record low road toll for 1998," the

release said.
</P>
<P>
A particularly disturbing aspect of January's road toll was
that 27
deaths occurred in head-on crashes, it added.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to popular belief, most head-on collisions are not
caused
by overtaking. They are a symptom of the much bigger problems of
speeding, drunk-driving and fatigue," the release said. 
</P>
