<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia Releases World War II War Crimes Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, February 1 (Xinhua) -- World War Two concentration camp
guard Nada Sakic, extradited from Argentina last November on war
crimes charges, was released from prison on Monday by the Croatian
judiciary authorities after three months of investigation.
</P>
<P>
A court statement said the state attorney's office decided to
drop criminal proceedings against her because there was not enough
evidence to prove guilt.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Sakic, 72, was suspected of torturing inmates to death
when she served as guard in the women's block of the Jasenovac
prison camp from 1942 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
A warrant issued in July accused her of "carrying out torture,
inhuman treatment of civilians, as well as terror, intimidation
and collective punishment of civilians."
</P>
<P>
During the world War II, tens of thousands of Serbs, Jews,
Gypsies and anti-fascist Croats were killed at Jasenovac, the most
notorious of more than 20 concentration camps run by Croatia's
Nazi puppet state.
</P>
<P>
However, prosecutors failed to find a single inmate who could
confirm the allegations against Mrs. Sakic after three months and
26 witnesses, the court statement said.
</P>
<P>
Their investigation also could not prove that Mrs. Sakic held
any position of authority after arriving at the camp at age 16.
</P>
<P>
Sakic fled Croatia when Nazi rule was crushed and lived in the
resort of Santa Teresita after arriving in Argentina in 1947.
</P>
<P>
Sakic's husband Dinko, 76, was extradited in June and is facing
a similar trial in Zagreb. He is accused of ordering, witnessing
and participating in the war crimes committed in the Jasenovac
camp, which he commanded between 1942 and 1944 and being
responsible for the death of at least 2,000 people at Jasenovac.
</P>
<P>
He remains in jail and his trial is expected in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav authorities have demanded the extradition of Nada
Sakic to put her on trial. However, Croatia has ruled out the
possibility of extraditing her as she is a Croatian citizen. Nada
Sakic has indicated her willingness to stay in Croatia after her
release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Are Cooks in Most Urban Chinese Households </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- A survey conducted in three
Chinese cities has shown that the female members of 79.4 percent
urban families do the cooking.
</P>
<P>
The study of 888 people in Xi'an, capital of Shaanxi Province,
Taiyuan in Shanxi Province, and Qingdao in Shandong Province found
that younger and middle-aged women did 44.7 percent of the daily
meal preparation, and older women, 34.7 percent of that work.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, which was done by the Beijing-based
Horizon Market Survey Company, male members of the family only do
the cooking during festivals or special gatherings, because they
consider cooking a sort of art form.
</P>
<P>
It was a tradition in China that men brought home the bacon
while women were in charge of household work, which included
preparing the meals and taking care of children.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays however, some Chinese women in cities are reluctant to
give up a job even after having had a child.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Demolish Rundown Buildings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is to demolish 2.6
million square meters of rundown and potentially dangerous
buildings to mark the 50th anniversary of the founding of New
China and to give the Chinese capital an improved, modern image.
</P>
<P>
According to officials with the municipality's environmental
improvement department, the project will be carried out in three
phases.
</P>
<P>
The first phase is to pull down buildings illegally built on
both sides of the 255 main streets within the urban area in the
early half of this year; the second stage will tackle 420,000
square meters around the outskirts, suburbs and tourist
attractions by the end of August; and finally those in the
remaining old hutongs, lanes and neighborhoods by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Rundown buildings that impede traffic, fire fighting units or
generally create an inconvenience in the daily life of the people
will be listed as top priority. Once they have been razed the land
will be used to create more green, grassy areas and improve the
infrastructure of the city.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the municipal government at the end of last year
showed that most such buildings took up a total of 7.33 million
square meters, mainly located in the outskirts, neighborhoods, and
the 255 alleys and hutongs within the urban area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
