<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Opens Commerce Ministers' Meeting in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) opened its Third Commerce Ministers'
Meeting here Tuesday morning in a bid to forge close economic
links among the seven member countries.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the two-day meeting, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
said SAARC member countries "need to develop a harmonized and
coordinated approach and strengthen our efforts to defend and
develop our economies" as their economies "are vulnerable to
natural and external economic shocks."
</P>
<P>
Although the Sixth SAARC Summit held in Sri Lanka in 1991
decided to set up the South Asian Preferential Trade Arrangements,
"its results are yet to be felt" and intra-SAARC trade continued
to be stagnant at around 3 percent of the total trade of the
member countries, she said.
</P>
<P>
She called for efforts to increase trade and commerce within
the regional grouping and intra-SAARC investment flows. "Surplus
funds from members of SAARC should flow into other member
countries... in the form of joint ventures and direct investment
preferably with buy-back arrangements," she said.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, a regional economic bloc comprising Bangladesh, India,
Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan and the Maldives, was
established in 1985. "The success achieved by SAARC to date has
been much less striking" compared with some other regional
economic groupings such as the European Union, Commerce Minister
Tofail Ahmed said.
</P>
<P>
For example, the intra-regional trade accounted for 3.6 percent
of the total trade of the region in 1995 and "no significant
improvement has occurred over the last three years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, the most liberal regime in the region, has been the
destination of around half of all intra-regional imports while
India has been the origin of about four-fifths of total
intra-regional exports, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Some 18 percent of Bangladesh's imports come from other SAARC
countries, but it could market only 1.7 percent of its exports
within the region, he complained. "Efforts have to be made not
only to increase the volume of intra-regional trade but also to
ensure a more equitable distribution of its benefits," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed also proposed that SAARC commerce ministers work out at
the meeting a common strategy for the World Trade Organization
Ministerial Conference scheduled to take place at the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
SAARC Secretary-General Nehal Rodrigo, commerce ministers from
Pakistan, Nepal, Bhutan, the Maldives and Sri Lanka, and India's
commerce secretary attended the inaugural session.
</P>
<P>
India's commerce minister is not participating in the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Likely to Enact New Law to Ban Trade Unions in Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- A new law is likely to be enacted
soon to ban trade unions in Bangladesh's banking sector including
the Bangladesh Bank, the country's central bank, the Bangladesh
Observer newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister is now drafting two separate bills
regarding the new law.
</P>
<P>
The two bills, one for banning trade union in the central bank
and another endorsing suspension of trade unions in the scheduled
banks, are expected to be placed by the finance minister in the
current session of the parliament, the report quoted official
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister is going to place the bills in the
parliament after evaluating the recommendations of the Task Force
(TF) which submitted its report on February 19 last year.
</P>
<P>
The activities of trade unions were severely hindering the
day-to-day affairs of all the banks in the country including the
central bank, according to the TF's report.
</P>
<P>
In the name of trade unions and the central bargaining agents
(CBAs), leaders of the trade unions and CBAs are virtually running
a parallel administration controlling posting, promotions and
transfers of the bank's employees and officials, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The TF said that discipline in the banking sector could be
restored by banning trade unions and CBAs for a period of at least
three year, adding that all the activities of the trade unions and
CBAs would be considered punishable offense during the period.
</P>
<P>
But the existing law does not allow the government to stop the
activities of trade unions in the banks and other financial
institutions, the press report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suicide Rate Drops 15 Percent in S. Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Suicide rate in Sri Lanka,
which was viewed among the highest in the world, has decreased by
15 percent from 7,364 cases in 1993 to 6,228 in 1997 according to
the latest police statistics.
</P>
<P>
This figure is expected to fall further by year 2000 according
to projections made by the Special Presidential Task Force on the
Prevention of Suicide.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Task Force said that there was much greater
awareness among the people about the problem. Further community
participation in activities against suicide had increased
significantly.
</P>
<P>
The high suicide rate has been largely blamed on failed love
affairs, extramarital pregnancy and joblessness.
</P>
<P>
Many community programs carried out for the elimination of
suicide had proved successful. It has also been observed that the
medical community specially in the peripheral hospitals in the
country were becoming increasingly sensitive to the issue.
</P>
<P>
New initiatives in acute management of poisoning have also
commenced at hospital level islandwide.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force experts noted that awareness programs had to be
targeted mainly at youth especially in rural precincts. According
to statistics the majority of suicide victims (around 30 percent)
belong to the 20 to 30 year age group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
