<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Parties Condemn NATO's Air Strike Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav political parties and
organizations on Monday vehemently condemned NATO's decision to
authorize the use of force against Yugoslavia over its handling of
the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian Socialist Party lodged a strong protest against
NATO, saying that the open military threat to an independent and
sovereign state runs counter to the wish of the international
community of seeking political solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The threat also constituted a violation of the United Nations
Charter because it serves as an open support to the ethnic
Albanian "separatists and terrorists " in Kosovo, it said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The NATO decision is not understandable but unacceptable, it
noted.
</P>
<P>
The Belgrade Municipal Commission of the Leftist Coalition
expressed its resentment to the NATO decision, saying that the
military threat was not only unreasonable, but also immoral.
</P>
<P>
Another Yugoslav party, the Serbian Radical Party, said the
NATO move was an aggressive interference in a sovereign state and
an open violation of the UN Charter.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, the Belgrade University Students Association
lodged a strong protest against the NATO authorization, urging
peace talks between the government and the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, the North Altantic Council authorized NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana to order air strikes against
Yugoslavia if the six-nation Contact Group deems them necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
