<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists: Gene Could Help Delay Menopause </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A new study has shown that
mice, which are missing a particular gene, have ovaries that
function for much longer than normal, avoiding the degeneration
associated with menopause.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston created
the strain of mice by disabling a gene called Bax. The mutant mice
have three times the number of ovarian follicles as normal mice,
according to a report in the February issue Nature Genetics.
</P>
<P>
"The research, which is far from application in humans, may
eventually lead to new techniques for delaying menopause and
reducing its associated health risks," said a statement from the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Tilly, the senior author of the report in Nature
Genetics, believes that it's too early to speculate about whether
scientists could extend ovarian life in women or what good that
might be.
</P>
<P>
The study is the first to find that follicle depletion and loss
of ovarian function, the cause of menopause, can be stopped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0245 </DOCNO>
