<HEADLINE> About 2,000 Romanian Children Die of AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Acquired Immune
Deficiency Syndromes (AIDS) have taken the lives of 2,210 people,
including 2,000 children, said the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Health Ministry figures showed Monday that 5,730 AIDS cases
have been reported in the country, including 5,040 child cases.
</P>
<P>
Last year alone, 130 adults and 500 children were tested HIV
positive.
</P>
<P>
Romania found its first AIDS patient in 1985 and it has now
become a European country where most patients are children.
</P>
<P>
Most child AIDS patients are victims of blood transfusion
conducted before 1990. But now HIV-virus-carrying mothers have
become the main source of infection to children. 
</P>
