<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Election Body Sets Campaign Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's General Election
Agency has scheduled the election campaign to run from May 18
through June 6, and banned the mobilization of the masses in order
to prevent clashes among party supporters.
</P>
<P>
The election agenda which included the campaign season has been
arranged to give ample time for the political parties to prepare
for the June 7 polls, the chairman of the agency, Minister of Home
Affairs Syarwan Hamid, told reporters here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"So what we have here is a tentative schedule starting from the
registration of political parties to the actual balloting and the
People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) General Session in November,"
he said after a meeting of the election agency leadership.
</P>
<P>
He said in accordance with the legislation on general
elections, political parties contesting the poll were required to
hold indoor campaign activities.
</P>
<P>
"Political parties will not be allowed to mobilize the masses
in open fields and party supporters will be barred from taking to
the streets. These measures are meant to prevent clashes and
violence like in the past," he was quoted by the Jakarta Post
Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also said around 30 out of the around 200 political parties
are expected to be eligible to contest the elections.
</P>
<P>
According to John Sani, deputy head of the agency, all
activities relating to and resulting from the June election will
be carried out in seven phases over a period of about seven months
starting February 1.
</P>
<P>
The first phase would be time for the registration and
screening of the political parties that would take part in the
elections. The time span would be February 1 to March 1.
</P>
<P>
The second phase would be for voters' registration and run from
March 18 to April 17.
</P>
<P>
During the third phase, March 1 to April 15, the parties would
name their nominees to district, provincial and national
legislative assemblies.
</P>
<P>
In the fourth phase, May 18 through June 6, the election
contestants would hold their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Asked to explain the time lapse of one month between the third
and fourth phases, Sani said that it would be used for
administrative processing activities.
</P>
<P>
The fifth phase would be polling and vote-counting at polling
stations on June 7. According to the head of public relations at
the Ministry of Home Affairs Herman Ibrahim, 13 days would be
required to finalize the vote-counting.
</P>
<P>
During the sixth phase, the results of the general elections
for the different legislatures would be formalized, namely June
20-26 for district legislative assemblies, June 27-July 2 for
provincial legislative assemblies and July 3-12 for the central
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The seventh phase would be for the oath-taking of members of
the various legislative assemblies, namely July 20 for district
legislative assemblies, July 25 for provincial legislative
assemblies and August 29 for the central parliament.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the Home Affairs Ministry observed this year's
election could not be done in 12 phases like the previous ones
because of the limited time available.
</P>
<P>
"While in the past, the 12 phases required one year and a half,
now we only have a few months," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
