<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Open Capital Link for Ailing SMEs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) is considering to set up a new board for small- and
medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) with lower listing requirements,
an SET official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With the new board, cash-strapped SMEs can look forward to
tapping the capital market, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The SET organized a seminar Monday, at which Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai promised to push for enactment of the Small- and
Medium-sized Enterprises legislation by the end of this year for a
big chunk of the country's real sector to tap the capital market.
</P>
<P>
There are about 130,000 SMEs in Thailand, which account for 98
percent of all registered factories. These SMEs employ 1.6 million
workers, or 50 percent of the industrial workforce, according to
government statistics.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposed legislation, an SME is a company with
no more than 50 million baht (1.39 million U.S. dollars) in
capital and employs no more than 200 workers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 50 billion baht (1.39 billion dollars) will be
available to increase SME liquidity. The funds will be used to
support the government's policy on recapitalization and debt
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
However, a top banker cautioned that it will not be easy to
recapitalize SMEs and restructure their debts because they
generally have high risks and investors are now more risk-averse.
</P>
<P>
Bantoon Lamsam, president of Thai Farmers Bank, warned that
tapping the capital market would be difficult or even impossible
for SMEs unless they undergo simultanous financial and risk
restructuring to increase efficiency and long-term
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
To increase the prospect of turning around SMEs, he said, there
should not be only debt or financial restructuring but also risk
restructuring given that SMEs generally have higher risks than
large enterprises due to higher funding costs, less technology
competitiveness, less management skills, less personnel
development and less transparency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
