<HEADLINE> Thai Exim Bank Wants More Businesses Covered by ADB Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Export-Import (Exim) Bank
of Thailand suggested that more businesses should be covered by
the Asian Development Bank's (ADB's) support facility, an Exim
Bank official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to stimulate liquidity in the market, the Exim Bank is
negotiating with ADB to expand the borrower target eligible for
the remaining 800 million U.S. dollar support facility from ADB.
</P>
<P>
The Exim Bank said the target should be expanded from only
narrowly-defined exporters, who directly export goods overseas, to
all businesses generating foreign currency, the official quoted
Exim Bank President Pridiyathorn Devakula as saying.
</P>
<P>
So far, ADB has approved a support facility of one billion
dollars to Thai exporters via the Exim Bank, who have only
utilized 200 million dollars of the total available.
</P>
<P>
The president said that as the liquidity of commercial banks
has improved significantly since the second half of last year,
commercial banks would not need additional supporting loans from
the ADB.
</P>
<P>
He said the Exim Bank aims to extend between 9-10 billion baht
(250-277.8 million dollars) in additional funds this year.
</P>
<P>
The Exim Bank this year will focus on exporters whose
businesses may have great potential but are facing financial
difficulties. These exporters' loan applications were mostly
rejected by commercial banks which are currently very cautious of
lending.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's economy this year depends heavily on exports since
internal demands will see no significant increase.
</P>
<P>
The government has predicted that the country's exports this
year could grow by four percent mainly from the automobile and
steel sectors.
</P>
<P>
Exports account for 44-45 percent of Thailand's gross domestic
product at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
