<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Deputy PM Backs Acceptance of Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister
and Chairman of the Serbian Renewal Movement Vok Draskovic on
Monday voiced his support for the Yugoslav government to accept
NATO's invitations to peace talks on Kosovo in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Draskovic told a press conference that although the government
had yet to decide whether to send a delegation to the talks, he
and his Serbian Renewal Movement definitely stood for a positive
response to the invitations.
</P>
<P>
Draskovic said the delegation dispatched by the Yugoslav
government should point out at the negotiating table that some of
the demands contained in the resolution passed by the foreign
ministers of the six-nation Contact Group for former Yugoslavia in
London last Friday were unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
He said the delegation should stick to the important principled
stand against establishing "Greater Albania," granting Kosovo
independence or turning Kosovo into "the third republic of
Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
When asked about the deployment of ground forces by NATO in
Kosovo, Draskovic said as long as the international delegates
abide by the U.N. Charter and international norms at the Paris
meeting, there is no need for the Yugoslav government to build up
anti-terrorist forces in Kosovo or for NATO to station troops
there.
</P>
<P>
Only when the international delegates explicitly condemn
terrorism and do not back Kosovo's independence will those who
depend on NATO ground forces for the establishment of a "Greater
Albania" discard their illusion, said Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
The six-nation Contact Group, make up of the United States,
Russia, France, Britain, Germany and Italy, issued an ultimatum on
January 29 in London urging the warring sides in Kosovo to start
peace talks on February 6 and reach agreement within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
On the following day, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana
threatened military intervention in Kosovo if the conflicting
parties failed to fulfill the demands of the Contact Group.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who
chaired the Contact Group meeting, delivered their demands to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade. Milosevic
responded coolly to the ultimatum, saying that the Republic of
Serbia and the Yugoslav government will reply after having
carefully studied the Contact Group's statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
