<HEADLINE> Court in Guangdong Improves Work Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 2 (Xinhua)-- The Supreme Court of south
China's Guangdong Province improved its efficiency levels in 1998
with an increasing number of cases being resolved.
</P>
<P>
Lu Botao, president of the court, in his report to the
provincial committee of the National People's Congress, revealed
that it had handled some 480,000 cases and reached verdicts in 410,
000 of them last year, representing an annual increase of 17
percent and 18 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
He attributed this to an anti-corruption move initiated in
February last year among court functionaries, which helped to
settle over 2,000 cases which had been in the system for a long
time, 482 cases which had been unduly delayed and 203 cases with
sentences considered unfair.
</P>
<P>
During the period, 92 court officials were investigated for
various corruption activities and four of them were sentenced.
Meanwhile, the court has cut its ties with 97 affiliated companies
to ensure law enforcement is conducted fairly and openly.
</P>
<P>
The court president added that it had worked closely with
police forces in fight against organized crime, such as armed
robberies and smuggling. 
</P>
