<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Won't Leave East Timor Abruptly: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will not abruptly
leave East Timor as Portugal did in 1975, should the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR) decide to grant independence to the
former Portuguese colony later this year, Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
"No, we will not do that," said Alatas Monday when asked by
reporters whether Indonesia will do what Portugal did in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Portugal abruptly abandoned its former colony following 400
years of colonization. Indonesia announced the integration of East
Timor into the country in 1976 and declared it as the 27th
province, but the United Nations has not recognized the move.
</P>
<P>
Alatas was speaking to reporters after he and other ministers
holding political portfolios met with President B.J. Habibie at
the Merdeka Palace here to discuss domestic and overseas reactions
to the latest move by the government.
</P>
<P>
In a surprise announcement last week, the government said it
will ask the MPR to grant independence to East Timor, if the
region rejects a special status for the area, together with
wide-ranging autonomy proposed by Jakarta now being discussed at
the U.N. sponsored talks.
</P>
<P>
"The president has asked me to continue monitoring (comments on
East Timor). I met him to convey a progress report on East Timor.
There are a lot of things I need to report to him, such as who
have made comments and what those comments were," Alatas was
quoted by the Indonesian Observer Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Alatas also reported about a planned
tripartite meeting between himself and his Portuguese counterpart
under the aegis of the U.N. secretary general.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to set a suitable date for the meeting because
the U.N. secretary general wants to hear directly from the
Indonesian foreign minister about Indonesia's latest stand on East
Timor," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
