<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Produce, Sell Gas from Yetagun by Year-End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will be ready by the end
of this year to produce and sell natural gas from the country's
Yetagun Field off southern Tanintharyi coast.
</P>
<P>
According to the Myanmar Energy Ministry sources, of the
67-kilometer onshore pipeline, 42 km has been laid, and of the
206-km offshore pipeline, 178 km has been connected.
</P>
<P>
Laying of the two pipelines at Kanbauk region in the
Tanintharyi division began in October last year.
</P>
<P>
The Yetagun gas field, constituted with four blocks, has been
explored and being developed by a foreign oil group made up of
Britain's Premier, Japan's Nippon, Thailand's PTTEP, Malaysia's
Petronas and Myanmar's state-run Oil and Gas Enterprise since
1990.
</P>
<P>
The gas field, located in the Andaman Sea at a depth of 101
meters and about 200 km away from the Myanmar coast, reportedly
has a reserve gas of 1.2 trillion cubic-feet and crude oil of 2
billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
According to a 30-year contract reached between the Petroleum
Authority of Thailand and the developers in March 1997, the
Yetagun gas will be sold to Thailand at 200 million cubic-feet
(5.6 million cubic-meters) per day.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the output of natural gas and
crude oil of Myanmar was 1.798 billion cubic-meters and 3.63
million barrels respectively in 1997-98 fiscal year, and the
figures in the first 10 months of 1998 went to 1.464 billion
cubic-meters and 2.865 million barrels separately.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the oil and gas sector reached 2.303
billion U.S. dollars in 46 projects at the end of October 1998 out
of 7.089 billion dollars' total foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Not to Sign Anti-Landmines Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will not be a
signatory to the Ottawa Anti-Landmines Treaty on the prohibition
of the use, stockpiling, production and transfer of mines and on
their destruction which will become effective on March 1, a
newspaper here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Government officials told The Island that they had explained to
the world community that the war situation in Sri Lanka's north
and east will not permit the government to enter into the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces fighting Tamil rebels heavily depend on
various types of mines, officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Asian diplomatic sources said that the entire seven nation
South Asia Association for Regional Cooperation group would not be
a part of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
However, the treaty has been ratified by more than 40 states,
the number required to activate the treaty, said Canada's new High
Commissioner Ruth Archibald.
</P>
<P>
Archibald told the paper that 133 countries signed the
convention beginning early December 1997 in Ottawa, of which 63
countries have already ratified or otherwise brought the Ottawa
convention into force in their own countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
