<HEADLINE> Peru's Foreign Reserves Rise Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Peru's hard currency reserves rose
to more than 9.4 billion U.S. dollars as of January 26 from 9.14
billion dollars at the end of 1998, the Central Bank said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The hike is due chiefly to the increase of net banking assets
reaching 417 million dollars, boosting reserves to over 9.1
billion dollars at the end of last year, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
In July 1990, Peru's foreign reserves were 150 million dollars
in the red, but they later started a continuous recovery, reaching
more than 10 billion dollars in 1997. 
