<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Urges U.N. to Prevent NATO Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav government urged
the United Nations Security Council on Monday to convene a special
meeting and take appropriate measures to prevent "NATO armed
aggression" against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
It made the call after the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (
NATO) authorized its secretary-general to decide when to use force
against Yugoslavia over its handling of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The government said in a statement that the NATO decision is "
an open threat to the sovereignty and integrity of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
"It is a violation of the principles of the United Nations
Charter", said the statement carried by the official Tanjug news
agency.
</P>
<P>
As a regional military organization, the statement said, NATO
does not have authorization from the U.N. Security Council, or
have the right to use force against a sovereign and independent
country.
</P>
<P>
"The NATO threat not only violated the basic principles
governing international relations, but also damaged the legal
foundation of world peace and security," it said.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, NATO authorized its secretary-general Javier
Solana to decide when to use air strikes to force the warring
sides in Kosovo to make peace.
</P>
<P>
Solana said on Monday that NATO forces were ready for any
military actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
