<HEADLINE> China's Auto Industry Growing Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 26 (Xinhua) -- China's auto industry kept
growing steadily in the first 11 months of 1998, according to the
National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures offered by the bureau show that Chinese
manufacturers produced 290,500 buses, 466,300 cars and 701,000
trucks between January and November last year, representing an
annual growth of 31.8 percent, 4.7 percent and 2.3 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the output of motorcycles dropped 16 percent to 7.2
million, according to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of Chinese have taken cars as their major
means of transportation, and several banks have extended loans to
individuals for car purchase.
</P>
<P>
The figures released by the bureau also indicate that the
output of bicycles also suffered a hefty fall of 15.5 percent to
21 million in the 11 months. Bicycles are still the most important
means of transportation for urban residents in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
