<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland's Zloty Devalues by 1.4 Percentage Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Poland's currency, the zloty,
lost 1.4 percent in value, falling to 3.736 to the U.S. dollar on
Monday, compared to last Friday.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest devaluation of the Polish currency so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the zloty had stood firm against the U.S. dollar at
3.5 to one.
</P>
<P>
Although it plummeted to 3.8 against the U.S. dollar last
August at the height of the Russian financial crisis, it rebounded
very soon to the normal level of 3.45.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's financial turmoil also had little impact on the zloty,
which only registered a slight drop in value.
</P>
<P>
The latest devaluation is mainly due to Poland's domestic
troubles, according to banking sources.
</P>
<P>
The one-month strikes and demonstrations by peasants and
medical personnel made foreign investors quite uncertain about the
economic prospect of the country. And as a result, they begin to
sell the zloty. Even the Bank of Poland followed suit.
</P>
<P>
Some warned that if the zloty devalued further, some foreign
investors could consider withdrawing from the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
