<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Team Studies Brazil's Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A technical team from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) continued its meetings on Monday
with Brazilian officials to assess the crisis affecting the
largest economy in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Amaury Bier, the finance ministry's economic policy director,
said that the IMF team has split into two groups, one for
examining fiscal policies and macroeconomic indicators, and the
other for reviewing balance of payments, money supply and bank
system supervision.
</P>
<P>
Bier said the assessment is preliminary to talks on Brazil's
economic goals scheduled for the next few days with the
participation of IMF's chief economist Stanley Fisher, who is due
to arrive on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bier said that due to the review of the goals, the IMF could
postpone until the end of February its second tranche of about 9
billion dollars from the 41.5 billion U.S. dollar international
credit granted to Brazil in November.
</P>
<P>
In December, Brazil received 9 billion dollars from the IMF and
used it to bolster its sagging currency reserves, now at 36
billion U.S. dollars, down from 74 billion dollars registered last
July. A second installment might help restore investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team arrived in Brazil last Saturday to review the pact
reached last November with Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
