<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Celebrates St Trypon's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Wine producers and viticulturists
throughout Bulgaria celebrated the tradition of St Trypon's Day on
Monday, hoping the patron saint of wine would bring a good harvest
and rebuild the country's wine industry.
</P>
<P>
In the capital of Sofia, a ceremony was held in the cellar of
the National Wine Quality Control Institute to honor the St Trypon
where two Bulgarian wines, Mavroud and Cabernet, were named "St
Trypon" and "St Valentine".
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's Trade and Tourism Minister Valentin Vassilev
attended the vine-cutting ceremony held in the 120-year-old cellar
of the institute.
</P>
<P>
Vassilev cut a vine in the yard of the institute, a ritual
viticulturists perform on St Trypon's Day.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador Chen Delai and 12 other foreign ambassadors
to Sofia attended the ceremony. They tried some organic Cabernet
wines produced without the use of pesticides or preservatives, and
the cellar's 44-year-old brandy.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to its favorable climate and soil conditions, Bulgaria
has a long history of wine production and most of its wine is
exported.
</P>
<P>
However, many vineyards across the country have been laid waste,
but vine acreage is increasing again after years of destructive
agricultural policies.
</P>
<P>
Now the country is determined to boost its wine industry.
</P>
<P>
Ventsislav Vurbanov, the agricultural minister, said while
attending the St Trypon's Day feast in the city on the Danube that
the future of wine-growing depends on new vine planting.
</P>
<P>
To encourage new vine planting, he said, the Agricultural State
Fund will provide about 150 billion leva (260 million U.S. dollars)
this year to help viticulturists and open new credit sources.
</P>
<P>
But vine-growers should show more enterprise to recover the
industry, Vurbanov added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
