<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Investors in Bulgaria Insured Against Currency Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Overseas Private Investment
Corporation (OPIC) of the U.S. government will provide insurance
to U.S. investors in Bulgaria that will pay out in case there is
trouble converting the local currency leva into U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The move places Bulgaria on an equal footing with Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic, which all benefit from sizable
American investment.
</P>
<P>
The OPIC has already received 20 letters of investment intent,
said Stuart Eizenstat, U.S. Deputy Secretary of State for Economic
and Business Affairs, who is co-chairman of the high-level
Bulgarian-American economic working group. The priorities of
bilateral cooperation are infrastructure, environment and the
energy industry.
</P>
<P>
The chief of the Bulgarian Foreign Investment Agency, Ilian
Vassilev, who also participated in the working group, said the
OPIC will provide insurance against deterioration of the host
country's ability to convert investors' income from the local
currency into U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But he added that Bulgaria had solid foreign currency reserves
and there was no danger that investors would be unable to convert
their currency.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the meeting of the working group were
representatives of 26 Bulgarian and 10 U.S. government
institutions. Along with Eizenstat, the co-chairman of the group
is Bulgarian Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Bozhkov.
</P>
<P>
The working group's 1999 agenda includes helping Bulgaria
stabilize its judicial system with the aid of the syllabus of the
institute for magistrates' training. The United States will also
offer technical assistance in preparing and implementing the legal
reform with the view to improving Bulgaria's trade and investment
climate.
</P>
<P>
According to Eizenstat, the U.S. government will provide 39
million dollars to assist Bulgarian reforms in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
