<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Production of Energy Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- China suffered an annual drop
of 3.3 percent in the production of energy during the January-
November period last year, according to the latest figures
released by the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Total energy output in the 11 months stood at 1.05 billion tons
of standard coal equivalent, of which 1.06 million tons were
produced in November, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Production of coal dropped by 4.9 percent to 1.03 billion tons,
that of crude oil decreased by 0.7 percent to 146.8 million tons
and that of natural gas dropped by 0.6 percent to 19.8 billion
cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the output of electricity increased by 2.5 percent
to 1.02 trillion kwh. In a breakdown, it was composed of 825.2
billion kwh of thermal power, up 1.6 percent; 179 billion kwh of
hydro-electric power, up 5.6 percent; and 13.5 billion kwh of
nuclear power, up 1.6 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
