<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Strives for Improvement of Health Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been implementing
its national health policy and plans compatible with the country's
situation to materialize the social objective of uplifting health
and fitness.
</P>
<P>
A five-year National Health Plan from 1996 to 2001 is under
implementation through the strategies of programming community
health care, disease control, hospital care, environmental health,
health systems development and management.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 50 detailed work projects of these six broad
programs are being carried out, of which priority is given and
serious attention is paid to primary health care, rural health
care, promoting health care systems equally in urban and rural
areas, and cooperation of not only government organizations but
also social, private and joint venture ones.
</P>
<P>
Since late 1988, a total of 95 new hospitals have been opened
and 72 old hospitals upgraded with 56 rural health care centers,
20 regional health centers and 76 clinics added to provide health
care services in villages and the areas lagging behind.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar also pays attention to the nurturing of adequate number
of doctors, specialists and technicians as human resources
development, while working out more programs such as health
research paper-reading sessions, medical seminars and development
of new medical curriculum for promotion of medical science and
health education.
</P>
<P>
The government also encourages local doctors to continue
further studies to attain higher degrees.
</P>
<P>
To promote its health services for the entire population,
Myanmar introduced a cost-sharing health care system beginning
last year on account of the government's limited ability to bear
all the national health expenditures alone and has set up trust
funds at some major hospitals to provide health services to poor
and needy patients.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Myanmar pays attention to the development of
traditional medicine, opening up more related hospitals and
treatment and research centers, and nurturing more traditional
medicine practitioners.
</P>
<P>
The country has also been carrying out prevention and control
programs against diseases of malaria, AIDS and polio, while
disseminating health education through mass media to promote
public awareness of health information and knowledge.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, up to the 1997-98 fiscal
year, there registered 734 hospitals with 28,943 beds, 350
dispensaries, 1,410 rural centers and 348 maternal and child
health centers in the entire country with 14,007 doctors, 11,840
nurses and 9,524 midwives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
