<HEADLINE> Chinese Health Minister Concerns About Leprosy Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- About 120,000 handicapped
Chinese who have recovered from leprosy are expecting love and
concern from the entire society, China's Health Minister said in a
recent visit to leprosy hospital.
</P>
<P>
"Society should pay more attention to and be on good terms with
people who have recovered from the disease, instead of
discriminating against them," Zhang Wenkang said during his visit
to the hospital in Nanjing, east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Zhang urged governments at all levels and the public not only
to provide financial and policy support for patients' treatment,
but also to help recovered patients find jobs.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 of the handicapped patients were homeless and
lived in special houses, today's China Daily quoted Li Wenzhong,
an expert with the Skin Disease Institute of Chinese Academy of
Medical Sciences, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide efforts would be made to achieve an incidence rate
lower than one per 100,000 people in 95 percent of Chinese
counties by the end of this century, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, about 85 percent of counties and cities had
lowered their leprosy incidence rates under the level. The number
of patients dropped to 4,045 in 1997 from 500,000 in the 1950s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
