<HEADLINE> Yueyang Customs Office Stops Antimony Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Yueyang Customs Office in
central China's Hunan Province stopped an illegal shipment of
antimony bound to Thailand and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed company from neighboring Hubei Province submitted a
customs declaration for 80 tons of aluminum alloy, with an ensuing
routine check by Yueyang customs officers revealing that the
contents of the shipment failed to conform with documents
presented.
</P>
<P>
A test revealed that the shipment in fact contained antimony
with a purity of over 96 percent. The Customs office noted that
antimony exports must be licensed and taxed in accordance with
related regulations.
</P>
<P>
China currently accounts for over 70 percent of the world's
total antimony production. China's 20 largest antimony producers
have signed an agreement last year to join in the campaign against
antimony smuggling in order to help maintain normal prices on the
international market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
