<HEADLINE> China's Textile Industry Sees Declining Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- China's textile industry, which
is under an overhaul, witnessed a decline in production in the
first eleven months last year, according to the National Bureau of
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The output of yarn dropped 2.5 percent to 4.64 million tons
from the same period of 1997, and that of cloth fell 5.0 percent
to 15.6 billion meters.
</P>
<P>
Of the total cloth production, pure cotton cloth declined 7.3
percent to 7.5 billion meters, cotton and chemical fiber blend
went down 6.8 percent to 5.3 billion meters, while pure chemical
fiber grew 6.3 percent to 2.7 billion meters.
</P>
<P>
The January-November period also saw a decline in the
production of knitting wool and woolen piece goods. The output of
knitting wool decreased 8.8 percent to 285,300 tons and that of
woolen piece goods dropped 11.3 percent to 235 million meters.
</P>
<P>
The output of silk also fell 9.6 percent to 56,100 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has been restructuring the textile
industry since early last year, cutting outmoded spindles for both
cotton and wool spinning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
