<HEADLINE> 180 Police Offices Torched, Vandalized in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 180 police offices
have been torched and vandalized since riots erupted in many parts
of Indonesia last year, said Lt. Gen. Roesmanhadi, chief of the
Indonesian Police.
</P>
<P>
The 180 offices of police sectors and resorts have not
undergone repair due to funding difficulties, he said at a working
meeting in Bandung, capital of West Java, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by deputy chiefs of police districts
across the country.
</P>
<P>
Roesmanhadi asked each province to submit a plan for
operational budgets, including those needed to repair the police
offices attacked by mobs.
</P>
<P>
He said the police must also replace shields which were damaged
during encounters with rioters.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly 100 to 200 police shields in each police resort must be
replaced with new ones," he was quoted by Antara News Agency
Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Roesmanhadi said: "We are even thinking of operational costs
for police officers to safeguard against riots in several parts of
the country."
</P>
<P>
To solve the funding problems, the police began efforts to
maximize revenues from public services, including from the
issuance of driving licenses and vehicle plates, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
