<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment up 6.4 Percent in Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Economy Minister Jorge Leiva
said Monday that foreign investment in Chile surpassed 6.5 billion
U.S. dollars in 1998, a 6.4 percent increase over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Leiva said the growth shows the confidence of foreign investors
in the Chilean economy, despite last year's Asian and Russian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
A total of 39.9 percent of foreign capital went into mining,
followed by services with 33.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Foreign Investment Committee approved 443
investment projects, 172 of which were new projects worth more
than 3.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Canada was the biggest investor country with 23.6 percent of
the total, followed by the United States with 21.8 percent and
Spain 11.6 percent. 
