<HEADLINE> China Making More Efforts to Protect Wetlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is
expected to take more vigorous actions to protect its wetland
resources, said a forestry official yesterday, on the eve of the
third annual World Wetlands Day, which is being celebrated today.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, measures will be taken to
regulate exploitation. National standards and systems for
evaluating environmental damage caused by the abuses of wetlands
are expected to be established.
</P>
<P>
The government is working on a draft of the China Wetlands
Protection Plan. It expects to increase state funding for
protection plans and to implement a comprehensive survey of
wetland resources, said Zhang Jianlong, director of the Department
of Wild Animals and Plant Protection of the State Forestry
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said China will establish 180 wetland ecosystem reserves
by 2000, up from the existing 148 reserves. Of the 148 protected
zones, seven of them are listed by an international convention on
protecting wetland resources of international significance.
</P>
<P>
Major threats to China's wetlands come from human incursion,
worsening pollution, damages to ecological diversity, degeneration
of the wetland ecological functions and abuse of it as a resource,
said an expert.
</P>
<P>
China has the largest wetland areas in Asia at about 65 million
hectares, or 10 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands in north China and in the middle and lower reaches of
the Yangtze River have deteriorated, forcing migratory birds to
change their migratory behavior from relying on inland China to
relying on the coastal areas of east China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
