<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Growth in Steel Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- China witnessed growing steel
production in the first eleven months last year with output
increasing 6.5 percent from a year earlier to 103.92 million tons,
according to the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The output of steel products between January and November last
year amounted to 94.5 million tons, up 9.4 percent on an annual
basis, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the output of light rails plunged 37
percent to 123,600 tons, and that of large rolled steel went down
by 20.5 percent to 955,400 tons.
</P>
<P>
Production of pig iron grew by 6.7 percent to 107 million tons
in the January-November period.
</P>
<P>
The period also saw an increase in the output of non-ferrous
metals. The output of aluminium oxide hit 3.1 million tons, up 13.
5 percent, and that of aluminium products 1.2 million tons, up 6.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the production of ferro alloys dropped by 4.2
percent to 3.1 million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
