<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President-Elect Announces Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's President-elect
Hugo Chavez Monday announced his 10-member cabinet on the eve of
his swearing-in ceremony.
</P>
<P>
General Raul Salazar, a former military attache in Washington,
was named as defense minister. He was chosen for the post even
before Chavez's election.
</P>
<P>
Veteran Communist Party leader Luis Miquilena was named
interior and justice minister. Miquilena had been one of Chavez's
main allies since he finished his term in a military prison in
1994 after the failure of his attempted coup in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Maritza Izaguirre will retain her post in the
new cabinet, she is the only official from the former
administration. The New York-born Izaguirre is a 59-year-old
sociologist.
</P>
<P>
The second woman chosen by Chavez is Atala Uriana, an Indian
from the Guajira Guayu ethnic group, Venezuela's largest
indigenous group. Uriana, the first Indian ever appointed to a
government position, will head the environment ministry.
</P>
<P>
Lawyer Javier Elechiguerra was named federal attorney-general.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Gustavo Marquez Marin was appointed industry and
commerce minister.
</P>
<P>
Roberto Mandini was appointed director of the key state-run oil
company Petroleos de Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The new foreign minister is 69-year-old journalist Jose Vicente
Rangel, while another pressman, Alfredo Pena, 54, will head the
presidential office.
</P>
<P>
The education ministry will go to the former head of
postgraduate studies of Venezuela's Autonomous University, Hector
Navarro.
</P>
<P>
The new health minister is Gilberto Rodriguez Ochoa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
