<HEADLINE> Brazil Currency Recovers Significantly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's currency, the
real, on Monday climbed significantly after eight consecutive days
of losing value.
</P>
<P>
The dollar on Monday was traded at 1.91 reals, up from 2.06 at
Friday's close, which had plunged below the psychological barrier
of two to the dollar for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The real's rally came after statements by U.S. billionaire
George Soros and by Citibank Vice-President William R. Rhodes that
the weakening real had fallen too far given the strength of Brazil'
s economy.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the devaluation of the rate has been exaggerated, as
happened in Mexico in 1994-95 after the peso was allowed to float,
" Rhodes said at the World Economic Summit in the Swiss city of
Davos.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that a rise of exports earnings which takes place
at the start of every month also contributed to the real's
recovery due to a higher offer of dollars on the market. The real
has dropped 39 percent since the devaluations began on January 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
