<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Social Status (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, there are 106 convents housing 3,727 nuns in the
Tibet Autonomous Region. Most women with religious beliefs in
Tibet believe in the Tibetan form of Buddhism, while others
believe in Islam and Catholicism. Female clerics from various
religions in Tibet enjoy full liberty to conduct normal religious
activities, while all temples and convents are managed in a
democratic way.
</P>
<P>
Women in Tibet enjoy equal employment rights with men.
Currently, Tibet has some 477,000 female workers, accounting for
45.8 percent of the region's total employment, and 67.1 percent of
women above the age of 15 years in Tibet have a job.
</P>
<P>
According to 1997 statistics, there were 58,254 female workers
in cities and towns in Tibet, 35 percent of the region's total
urban workers. Tibetan women are hired in all major sectors of the
national economy, especially in ethnic handicrafts, finance,
tourism, health and medical care, education, culture and arts, and
post and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Female workers make up 45 percent of the total employees of the
ethnic handicraft sector in Tibet, and in areas like wool spinning,
tailoring and rug-knitting, the proportion of female workers is as
high as 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 10.53 percent of deputies to people's congresses at all
levels in the Tibet Autonomous Region are women. Among the
deputies to the 7th Autonomous Regional People's Congress, women
account for 20.09 percent, up by 0.09 percentage point compared
with the 6th Autonomous Regional People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The old Tibet had no female government employees, let alone
female officials. After the democratic reform, the state has
attached great importance to selecting and training women
officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Social Status (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are facts and
figures about the social status of women in the Tibet Autonomous
Region:
</P>
<P>
As a result of social progress, women in Tibet are gradually
gaining rights, opportunities and dignity of which they had been
deprived in the old Tibet, where the social system and cultural
tradition discriminated strongly against females. There is now an
obvious change of destiny for Tibetan women.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, by the end of 1997 there were
1.2184 million women in the Tibet Autonomous Region, making up 50.
2 percent of the region's total population. Apart from some 1.12
million women from the Tibetan ethnic group, women there also come
from 30 other ethnic groups, including Han, Hui, Lhoba, Monba,
Mongolian, Naxi and Sherpa.
</P>
<P>
In the old Tibet, women were denied political and educational
rights. They were subject to excessive economic exploitation by
land owners and to numerous social and religious discriminations.
At that time, a pregnant woman had to give birth to her child in a
sheepfold according to religious taboos, and as a result the
mortality rate for new-borns then was as high as 430 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
In March 1959, the central government of China launched a
democratic reform in Tibet, bringing emancipation to the over one
million serfs and slaves there, who won not only personal freedom
but also the right to subsistence and development. All ethnic
groups in Tibet gained equality, while women there were also
granted equal legal status with men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Province Helps 150,000 laid-offs Relocate Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 150,000 laid-off workers
form the State-run enterprises in Shaanxi Province have been re-
employed after receiving a variety of training programs.
</P>
<P>
As one of the country's major industrial bases, there are a
total of 10,000 State-owned enterprises in the fields of machinery,
electronics, national defense and steel.
</P>
<P>
But 60 percent of these enterprises have been in the red in
recent years and forced to dismiss 306,100 workers.
</P>
<P>
To help the enterprise laid-offs re-locate jobs, the local
government has hosted a lot of training programs on technical
skills since early last year.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, concerned labor department provides a series
of favorable policies to ensure a priority for the laid-off when
they try to open private businesses or are re-employed by local
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
