<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Social Status (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Tibet Autonomous Region now has 48 maternity and child care
centers, while 108 hospitals at and above the county level now
have departments of gynecology and obstetrics. Modern delivery
methods are also available for 50.8 percent of child-bearing women
in Tibet, and the rate reaches 100 percent in Lhasa, the regional
capital.
</P>
<P>
The mortality rate for child-bearing women in Tibet has dropped
to 70 per 10,000 from 500 per 10,000 in the early years of the
democratic reform, while the infant mortality rate has also
sharply decreased to 33.77 per thousand from 430 per thousand. The
average life expectancy for women in Tibet has also risen to 65
years from 36 years before the democratic reform.
</P>
<P>
A survey among women in Lhasa shows that 82 percent of the
married women in the city have chosen their spouses according to
their own will, and 20 percent of them have a decisive say in
arranging household expenditures. In addition, some 48.5 percent
of Lhasa households decide family financial affairs through
friendly consultation between husbands and wives.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, women were taking charge of major family affairs in
some 9.57 percent of the 402,100 households in the Tibet
Autonomous Region, a rate higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
At present, the state policy of family planning is only
practiced among some 12 percent of the region's total population,
while farmers and herdsmen in the region, who account for 88
percent of the regional population, are not subject to this policy.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are 8,160 women's federation organizations in
the rural and pastoral areas of Tibet, with over 1,330 officials
at the township level and some 11,170 at the village or urban
neighborhood level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Social Status (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By July 1997, there were nearly 20,000 female officials in
government departments at all levels in the Tibet Autonomous
Region, 31 percent of the regional total. Women accounted for 10.
94 percent of the leading officials at and above the county level.
Among all the female officials, 69.7 percent were Tibetans and
members of other ethnic minorities. Women also made up over 20
percent of officials in various legislative bodies in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the proportion of female teachers in schools at
various levels varied from 35 to 55 percent, and several dozen
headteachers in primary and middle schools in the region were
female.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that at present, Tibet has 13,312 female
scientific and technological personnel, 41.4 percent of the region'
s total, and among them 93 are in senior professional or technical
positions.
</P>
<P>
The Tibet Autonomous Region now has more than 20 noted female
writers and painters, some 20 famous female singers, and a dozen
female dancers with a national reputation. The number of female
artists from Tibet winning various domestic and foreign artistic
awards has to date exceeded 50.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, 71.32 percent of the school-age girls in
Tibet had entered schools, while the number of female university
students reached 1,206, 37.69 percent of the region's total. The
number of women graduating from middle schools, technical schools
and universities totaled 12,930.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the state has set up 5,453 teaching
classes in Tibet's rural and pastoral areas to fight illiteracy.
Some 496,911 women have studied in these classes and 134,423 of
them are no longer illiterate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
