<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Students Contest to Mark May 4th Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua)-- Chinese students are expected to
look to the future while celebrating the 80th anniversary of the
May Fourth Movement, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
According to this Beijing-based English newspaper, a national
competition challenging the students' abilities to create and
innovate in honor of the May Fourth Movement, an event that began
in 1919, was begun yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
College and middle school students from across the country are
expected to participate in the contest, initiated by All-China
Students' Federation jointly with China Science Association and
China's Communist Youth League.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the contest are required to create designs
concerning themes such as prospective scientific developments and
breakthroughs in the 21st century, new products and manufacturing
processes for industry, agriculture or service sector activities,
lifestyles and education in the new epoch, and possible solutions
to major problems facing mankind in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The designs are expected to be expressed using various media
including articles, pictures, models, or computers.
</P>
<P>
Deng Yong, secretary-general of the students' federation, said
the contest is designed to cultivate and encourage youths to
create and invent on the basis of their knowledge.
</P>
<P>
The contest's finals will be held in May at Beijing University,
birthplace of the May Fourth Movement.
</P>
<P>
The movement, launched in 1919, was an anti-imperialist, anti-
feudal, political and cultural movement influenced by the Russian
October Revolution and was led by intellectuals influenced by
rudimentary understandings of Communist ideology, the paper said.
</P>
