<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Reserves Total 36 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's currency reserves
totaled 36.1 billion U.S. dollars last Friday, a central bank
statement said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement shows that the country's currency reserves
remained at the same level in the past two weeks, countering
rumors that they were dwindling due to capital flight in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
In an agreement signed last year with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) to receive a 41.5 billion dollars rescue
package, the Brazilian government pledged to maintain the reserves
at a minimum level of 20 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bank did not disclose the amount of cash it keeps on Monday,
but analysts estimated it at 35.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
To curb rumors about massive capital flight, the central bank
suspended its daily reports on the amount of the country's
exchange operations, which remained negative last months. Starting
from Monday, the bank will issue report every two weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
