<HEADLINE> Italian Premier Announces New Funds to Southern Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'
Alema said on Monday that in the coming five years, the southern
region of Italy can draw on funds of 120 trillion lire (70.6
billion U.S. dollars) in construction of infrastructure from the
central government.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Sicily Monday, D'Alema affirmed that the
southern region of Italy which links to poverty and Mafia, can
change face in five years if there is political stability with a
convergence of commitments.
</P>
<P>
He said that the fate of the government is bound to employment
and economic development as criteria for its success or lack of
success.
</P>
<P>
He also said that "this is not a dream book but something we
can do to create a new season of economic development through
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, D'Alema said that in the past, "funds from the
central government often permitted corruption and the enrichment
of the Mafia," but adding that this use of aid will certainly not
be continued.
</P>
<P>
"Thus a moral battle will be needed to teach young people to
reject crime and violence, to create a way of thinking against
easy riches," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
