<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Mulls Response to India's Indication on Test Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
considering backing away from its opposition to World Bank loans
for India as New Delhi indicated its willingness to sign an
international nuclear test ban treaty by a specific date, the
State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Progress has been made" during U.S.- India negotiations on
nuclear issues last week and as a result Washington is
"considering an appropriate response," State Department
spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We have said all along that our sanctions policy would be
adjusted based on progress in nonproliferation negotiations.
Progress has been made in these most recent negotiations and
We're consulting with Congress and other members of the
international community on how to respond to movement in the
right direction in terms of the comprehensive test ban," Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
Asked to define movement in the right direction, he said:
"With respect to the signing of the Comprehensive Test Ban ...
we receive some encouraging indications on the timing."
</P>
<P>
The United States and other major powers have been pressuring
India and Pakistan to sign the nuclear test ban treaty since
India and then Pakistan conducted nuclear tests in May 1998,
triggering fears of a regional arms race.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi and Islamabad told the U.N. General Assembly in
October 1998 that they would work toward successful completion
of the pact by September 1999, but Washington has wanted a specific
signing date from both countries. Some $1.7 billion in World Bank
loans to India have been on hold because of international
outrage over the tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Largest Bank Created by Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's two leading banks
announced Monday that they have agreed to merge, creating a
largest bank in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Byblos Bank and Banque Libanaise pour le Commerce (BLC) signed
on the merger agreement and thus the largest banking group in
Lebanon and one of the leading financial institutions in the
region is created," said a statement issued jointly by the two
banks.
</P>
<P>
The combined bank will operate under the name of Byblos and
become Lebanon's largest bank in terms of deposits which are
estimated at 360 million U.S. dollars, assets which reach 4.4
billion dollars, in addition to market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
The new Byblos Bank will also have the country's largest
network of branches, 82 in Lebanon and eight abroad.
</P>
<P>
The deal will be carried out after the Abou Jaoude family,
which owns 53 percent stake of the BLC, sold their shares to
Byblos for around 110 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The BLC, which is valued at 215 million dollars, will be
represented by two seats of the 12-member board of the new entity,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Francois Bassil, president of the Byblos, said at a news
conference after the signing ceremony that the tie-up will make
the bank play a more efficient role in the country and the region
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
He added that the merger will also enable the bank to serve
every Lebanese family, small- and medium-sized companies across
the country.
</P>
<P>
According to Lebanon's law, the merger still needs the
ratification of general assemblies of the both banks and the
Central Bank which has been encouraging Lebanon's 70 banks to
consolidate.
</P>
<P>
The BLC, founded in 1949 by Abou Jaoude family, has a branch in
Paris and four in the United Arab Emirates in addition to 35 in
Lebanon. Its total assets at the end of last year stood at 930
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
With total assets of 3.46 billion dollars and 55 branches,
Byblos Bank is known for its retail banking such as housing loans
and credit cards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
