<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Gov't Sector Workers Win Pay Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- More than a million public
sector workers won above inflation pay rises in the government's
public sector pay awards Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nurses were awarded a rise of 4.7 percent across the board --
inflation stands at 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
But some workers did far better than others. The minimum
starting salary for nurses will jump by 12 percent to 14,400
pounds (23,700 U.S. dollars) from 1 April.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet approved pay awards for the 1.3 million public
sector employees, including teachers, doctors and judges, last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a written Commons answer, Prime Minister Tony Blair said,
"In the Comprehensive Spending Review, the government made it
clear public sector pay settlements would need to be fair,
affordable and consistent with the targets we have set."
</P>
<P>
He said he was confident the new awards were in line with these
criteria and "the government's prudent and disciplined approach to
public spending and its commitment to delivering high-quality
public services and low inflation."
</P>
<P>
The average pay increase for public sector workers in the
spending review is 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the education sector, some primary school head teachers are
receiving up to 9 percent, with secondary heads getting a 6
percent boost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
