<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of People Fleeing Guinea-Bissau's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people are fleeing
the capital of Guinea-Bissau as heavy shelling in Bissau is
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Shelling began early Monday morning in the government-held part
of the city and continued through the whole morning, reports
reaching here quoted U.N. World Food Program spokesman Wagdi
Othman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of Bissau's population of 300,000 was fleeing the city
toward port areas and the interior after the rebels announced on
a radio station that they would launch a final attack on the
capital by 1300 gmt Monday, said the spokesman from Abidjan, Cote
d'Ivoire, from where he was in contact with aid workers in
Guinea-Bissau.
</P>
<P>
He said aid workers had reported some civilian casualties in
the fighting with some soldiers of the west African peacekeeping
force of ECOMOG wounded.
</P>
<P>
There are 110 ECOMOG troops, mostly from Togo, in Guinea Bissau
as part of last November's peace accord and hundreds more were due
to arrive this week to replace the Senegalese and Guinean troops
backing President Joao Bernardo Vieira.
</P>
<P>
The fighting between dissident army troops and forces loyal to
Vieira has suspended the deployment of ECOMOG troops in the
country while a French navy ship carrying several hundred
peace-keepers to Bissau was forced to stay off shore because of
the fighting.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord signed in November last year in the Nigerian
capital of Abuja called for the withdrawal of foreign troops, a
peace-keeping ECOMOG deployment, a government of national unity,
and general elections in March this year.
</P>
<P>
The rebellion broke out last June because of the dismissal of
top military commander Ansumane Mane, who now is the rebel leader,
for allegedly arms smuggling for separatist fighters in the
southern Senegalese province of Casamance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
