<HEADLINE> No Guaranteed Kosovo Peace Talks: UK Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Monday that it
had no guarantee the peace talks between the warring Serbs and the
ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province of Kosovo would succeed.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot confirm that the talks which we seek will take place.
Nor can I guarantee that if they take place, they will succeed,"
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a statement read in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Contact Group on former Yugoslavia, which
comprises the United States, Britain, France, Italy, Germany and
Russia, summoned the two sides in Kosovo to hold peace talks in
France this week to avert all-out war in the southern Yugoslav
province.
</P>
<P>
Cook said Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) guerrillas, formed by
ethnic Albanians, would not be able to stop the talks by staying
away.
</P>
<P>
He warned Yugoslavia at the same time that NATO was ready to
act if it refused to attend the talks, which will last a maximum
of two weeks.
</P>
<P>
He also stated that possible air strikes could take place in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Cook made his speech in the parliament two days after he had
delivered the Contact Group's ultimatum to Yugoslav and Kosovo
leaders, which said NATO's threat of action applied to both sides.
</P>
<P>
He said neither side would have to give up its long-term goals
by attending the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
But he refused to rule out the chances of the province
eventually gaining full independence, which was opposed by both
Belgrade and the Contact Group.
</P>
<P>
"Those who want to see an independent Kosovo -- which does not
embrace the Contact Group -- can take this opportunity of creating
democratic structures which would create a political community
within Kosovo which could be ready, if that was the outcome at
some future date, to take that extra step," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990202.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Aims at Women's Full Participation in Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Two major documents
adopted in China in recent years have far-reaching effects on the
elimination of the various forms of discrimination against women,
according to a Chinese envoy here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations, made the remarks at the 20th session of the Committee on
the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women (CEDAW) in the
capacity of the head of the Chinese Delegation to the session.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin referred to the Law on the Protection of the
Rights and Interests of Women adopted in 1992 and the Program of
the Development of Chinese Women formulated in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The first document defines four principles, namely equality
between men and women, protecting the special interests of women,
gradually improving the social protection of women, and
prohibiting the discrimination against, and maltreatment and
torture of, women.
</P>
<P>
As China's first basic law to protect women, it sets out the
political, cultural, educational, labor and economic rights of
women, as well as their rights on marriage, family and the person.
</P>
<P>
The second document, also the first of its kind, was formulated
after the framework of the Platform for Action of the Fourth World
Conference on Women.
</P>
<P>
It is most effective in pushing governments at various levels
to take concrete steps for women's full participation in social
development, Qin said.
</P>
<P>
The CEDAW, formed after the U.N. Convention on the Eliminations
of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women adopted in 1979, is
now reviewing China's reports on the progress made in the
implementation of the convention.
</P>
<P>
The reports cover the period from 1989-1995.
</P>
<P>
Since China resumed the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong
on July 1, 1997, the implementation of the convention by the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) is put under
consideration by the CEDAW as a part of China's report.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law provides that SAR social, economic and legal
systems differ from those of the mainland, thus the report drafted
by SAR will be introduced separately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
